{"title_page": "Lake Usori", "text_new": "{{Infobox lake\n| name = Lake Usori <br> \u5b87\u66fd\u5229\u6e56\n| image = 08-8-22 Lake Usori.JPG\n| caption = \n| image_bathymetry = \n| caption_bathymetry = \n| location = [[Honsh\u016b]], [[Japan]]\n| coords = {{coord|41|19|00|N|141|05|20|E|type:waterbody_region:JP|display=inline,title}}\n| type = [[volcanic crater lake]]\n| inflow = \n| outflow = Shotsu River\n| catchment = \n| basin_countries = Japan\n| length = \n| width = \n| area = {{convert|2.68|km2|abbr=on}}\n| depth =\n| max-depth = {{convert|23.5|m|abbr=on}}\n| volume =\n| residence_time = \n| shore = {{convert|7.1|km|abbr=on}}\n| elevation = {{convert|209|m|ft|0}}\n| islands = \n| cities = \n| pushpin_map             = Japan Aomori Prefecture#Japan\n| pushpin_label_position  = <!-- left, right, top or bottom -->\n| pushpin_map_alt         = \n| pushpin_map_caption     = \n}}\n{{nihongo|'''Lake Usori'''|\u5b87\u66fd\u5229\u6e56|Usori-ko}} is a [[volcanic crater lake]] in northern [[Honsh\u016b]] island, [[Japan]]. It is also referred to as {{nihongo|'''Lake Usorisan'''|\u5b87\u66fd\u5229\u5c71\u6e56|Usorizan-ko}}. Located in the [[Shimokita Peninsula]] of [[Aomori Prefecture]], it is within the borders of the city of [[Mutsu, Aomori|Mutsu]] and [[Shimokita Hanto Quasi-National Park]].\n\nLake Usori is located in the volcanic Osorezan Mountains, of which the famed [[Mount Osore]] forms one portion. From the surrounding [[caldera]] walls, some ten streams drain into Lake Usori, but there is only one outlet, the 13.85 kilometer Shotsu River, which drains into the [[Tsugaru Strait]].\n\nThe lake is noted for the extreme acidity of its water, with an average [[pH]] of around 3.3 to 3.4.<ref name=\"satake1995wasp\">{{cite journal |last=Satake |first=Kenichi |last2=Oyagi |first2=Akira |date= 1995|title= Natural acidification of lakes and rivers in Japan: The ecosystem of Lake Usoriko (ph 3.4\u20133.8) |journal= Water, Air, & Soil Pollution |volume= 85|issue= 2|pages= 511\u2013516 |doi= 10.1007/BF00476880 }}</ref> Geologists attribute this to [[hydrogen sulfide]] seeping from the [[caldera]] bottom, forming [[sulfuric acid]] in the lake water. Due to its acidity, the lake is home to only one subspecies of Japanese dace,<ref name=\"toyoji1999zs\">{{cite journal |last=Satake |first=Kenichi |last2=Oyagi |first2=Akira |date= 1999|title= Acid Tolerance of Japanese Dace (a Cyprinid Teleost) in Lake Osorezan, a Remarkable Acid Lake |url= http://www.bioone.org/doi/pdf/10.2108/zsj.16.871 |journal= Zoological Science |volume= 16|issue= 6|pages= 871\u2013877 |doi= 10.2108/zsj.16.871 |access-date= }}</ref> along with several insect species. However, the lake is a noted spot for waterfowl.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons category-inline}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Usori}}\n[[Category:Lakes of Japan]]\n[[Category:Calderas of Japan]]\n[[Category:Volcanic crater lakes]]\n[[Category:Tourist attractions in Aomori Prefecture]]\n[[Category:Landforms of Aomori Prefecture]]\n[[Category:Mutsu, Aomori]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox lake\n| name = Lake Usori <br> \u5b87\u66fd\u5229\u6e56\n| image = 08-8-22 Lake Usori.JPG\n| caption = \n| image_bathymetry = \n| caption_bathymetry = \n| location = [[Honsh\u016b]], [[Japan]]\n| coords = {{coord|41|19|00|N|141|05|20|E|type:waterbody_region:JP|display=inline,title}}\n| type = [[volcanic crater lake]]\n| inflow = \n| outflow = Shotsu River\n| catchment = \n| basin_countries = Japan\n| length = \n| width = \n| area = {{convert|2.68|km2|abbr=on}}\n| depth =\n| max-depth = {{convert|23.5|m|abbr=on}}\n| volume =\n| residence_time = \n| shore = {{convert|7.1|km|abbr=on}}\n| elevation = {{convert|209|m|ft|0}}\n| islands = \n| cities = \n| pushpin_map             = Japan Aomori Prefecture#Japan\n| pushpin_label_position  = <!-- left, right, top or bottom -->\n| pushpin_map_alt         = \n| pushpin_map_caption     = \n}}\n{{nihongo|'''Lake Usori'''|\u5b87\u66fd\u5229\u6e56|Usori-ko}} is a [[volcanic crater lake]] in northern [[Honsh\u016b]] island, [[Japan]]. It is also referred to as {{nihongo|'''Lake Usorisan'''|\u5b87\u66fd\u5229\u5c71\u6e56|Usorizan-ko}}. Located in the [[Shimokita Peninsula]] of [[Aomori Prefecture]], it is within the borders of the city of [[Mutsu, Aomori|Mutsu]] and [[Shimokita Hanto Quasi-National Park]].\n\nLake Usori is located in the volcanic Osorezan Mountains, of which the famed [[Mount Osore]] forms one portion. From the surrounding [[caldera]] walls, some ten streams drain into Lake Usori, but there is only one outlet, the 13.85 kilometer Shotsu River, which drains into the [[Tsugaru Strait]].\n\nThe lake is noted for the extreme acidity of its water, with an average [[pH]] of around 3.3 to 3.4.<ref name=\"satake1995wasp\">{{cite journal |last=Satake |first=Kenichi |last2=Oyagi |first2=Akira |date= 1995|title= Natural acidification of lakes and rivers in Japan: The ecosystem of Lake Usoriko (ph 3.4\u20133.8) |journal= Water, Air, & Soil Pollution |volume= 85|issue= 2|pages= 511\u2013516 |doi= 10.1007/BF00476880 }}</ref> Geologists attribute this to [[hydrogen sulfide]] seeping from the [[caldera]] bottom, forming [[sulfuric acid]] in the lake water. Due to its acidity, the lake is home to only one subspecies of [[Japanese dace]],<ref name=\"toyoji1999zs\">{{cite journal |last=Satake |first=Kenichi |last2=Oyagi |first2=Akira |date= 1999|title= Acid Tolerance of Japanese Dace (a Cyprinid Teleost) in Lake Osorezan, a Remarkable Acid Lake |url= http://www.bioone.org/doi/pdf/10.2108/zsj.16.871 |journal= Zoological Science |volume= 16|issue= 6|pages= 871\u2013877 |doi= 10.2108/zsj.16.871 |access-date= }}</ref> along with several insect species. However, the lake is a noted spot for waterfowl.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons category-inline}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Usori}}\n[[Category:Lakes of Japan]]\n[[Category:Calderas of Japan]]\n[[Category:Volcanic crater lakes]]\n[[Category:Tourist attractions in Aomori Prefecture]]\n[[Category:Landforms of Aomori Prefecture]]\n[[Category:Mutsu, Aomori]]\n", "name_user": "GrayMudkip101", "label": "safe", "comment": "Removed link to nonexistent Wikipedia article (Japanese dace)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lake_Usori"}
{"title_page": "Inger Andersen (environmentalist)", "text_new": "{{Infobox officeholder\n|name         = Inger Andersen\n|image        = Inger Andersen (environmentalist, 2010, cropped).jpg\n|office1       = Executive Director of the [[United Nations Environment Programme]] (UNEP)\n|term_start1   = TBD*\n|succeeding1   = [[Joyce Msuya]] {{small|(Acting)}}\n|office2       = Director General, [[International Union for Conservation of Nature]] (IUCN)\n|term_start2   = January 2015 \n|predecessor2  = [[Julia Marton-Lef\u00e8vre]]\n|nationality  = [[Denmark|Danish]]\n|birth_date   = 1958\n|birth_name   = Inger la Cour Andersen\n|birth_place  = [[Jerup]], Denmark\n|alma_mater   = [[London Metropolitan University]] and [[School of Oriental and African Studies]]\n|website      = [https://www.iucn.org/about/senior-management/director-general Official biography] }}\n\n'''Inger Andersen''' (born 23 May 1958) is a [[Denmark|Danish]] [[economist]] and [[environmentalist]]. In February 2019, she was appointed as the Executive Director of the [[United Nations Environment Programme]] [[UNEP]]. <ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.unenvironment.org/news-and-stories/press-release/un-secretary-general-appoints-inger-andersen-denmark-executive|title=UN Secretary-General appoints Inger Andersen of Denmark as Executive Director of the UN Environment|website=UN Environment|language=en|access-date=2019-04-21}}</ref> \n\nPrior to her appointment, at UNEP, Andersen was Director General of the [[International Union for Conservation of Nature]] (IUCN),<ref>{{cite web|title=Inger Andersen named IUCN Director General|url=http://www.iucn.org/?18465/Inger-Andersen-named-IUCN-Director-General|website=IUCN|access-date=3 December 2014|date=2014-10-14}}</ref> Vice President for Sustainable Development at the [[World Bank]] and Head of the [[CGIAR]] Fund Council and then World Bank Vice President for the Middle East and North Africa <ref>{{cite web|title=Inger Andersen World Bank profile|url=http://blogs.worldbank.org/team/inger-andersen|website=World Bank|access-date=13 July 2017}}</ref> \n\n== Family, early life and education ==\nInger Andersen is the daughter of Aagot la Cour Andersen and Erik Andersen.<ref>{{cite web|title=69: Lyngby-Linienhttp|url=http://www.pierrelacour.dk/s-bog/69-lyngby.htm|accessdate=13 July 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20050525232335/http://pierrelacour.dk/s-bog/69-lyngby.htm|archive-date=25 May 2005|url-status=dead}}</ref> She is the granddaughter of Danish historian and archaeologist Vilhelm la Cour. Her brother was Hans la Cour, author and film maker, known in the world of sail sport <ref>{{cite web|title=Eight Bells ... Hans La Cour Andersen|url=http://www.sail-world.com/Australia/Eight-Bells--Hans-La-Cour-Andersen/62776?source=google.ch|website=Sail-World|access-date=13 July 2017}}</ref> and environmental documentaries. <ref>{{cite web|title=Hans la Cour|url=https://www.imdb.com/name/nm1750616/?ref_=tt_ov_dr|website=IMDb|access-date=13 July 2017}}</ref>\n \nAndersen was born in [[Jerup]], Denmark. She graduated from Midtfyns Gymnasium secondary school in 1977. Andersen obtained a BA in 1981 from the Polytechnic of North London (now [[London Metropolitan University]]) and in 1982 gained an MA degree from the [[School of Oriental and African Studies]] at [[University of London]], with a specialisation in development studies focusing on economics and development. <ref>{{cite web|title=World Bank experts: Inger Andersen|url=http://live.worldbank.org/experts/inger-andersen|website=World Bank|access-date=3 December 2014|date=2013-08-12}}</ref>\n\n== Career ==\nAndersen started her career in Sudan in 1982 where she worked initially as an English teacher under the UK funded English teachers programme. In 1985 she joined SudanAid, the development and relief arm of the [[Sudan Catholic Bishops' Conference]]. Her work focused on famine and drought relief, and rehabilitation. <ref>{{cite web|title=69: Lyngby-Linienhttp|url=http://www.pierrelacour.dk/s-bog/69-lyngby.htm|accessdate=13 July 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20050525232335/http://pierrelacour.dk/s-bog/69-lyngby.htm|archive-date=25 May 2005|url-status=dead}}</ref> <ref>{{cite web|title= Inger Andersen - \"We must continue work towards fairer and more sustainable world\"|url=http://sustainability.thomsonreuters.com/women/inger-andersen-must-continue-work-towards-fairer-sustainable-world/|website=Thomson Reuters|access-date=14 July 2017|date=2017-06-14}}</ref> <ref>{{cite web|title= World Bank names three new vice presidents at the End of its Biggest Lending Year Ever|url=http://www.worldbank.org/en/news/press-release/2010/07/01/world-bank-names-three-new-vice-presidents-end-biggest-lending-year-ever|website=World Bank|access-date=13 July 2017}}</ref>\n\n===United Nations===\nAndersen worked at the [[United Nations]] in New York for 12 years at the UN Sudano-Sahelian Office (UNSO), (now the Global Policy Centre on Resilient Ecosystems and Desertification based in Nairobi<ref>{{cite web|title=Global Policy Centre on Resilient Ecosystems and Desertification|url=http://www.undp.org/content/undp/en/home/ourwork/global-policy-centres/sustainable_landmanagement/integrated_drylandsdevelopmentprogramme.html|accessdate=13 July 2017}}</ref>) where she worked on drought and [[desertification]] issues. In 1992, she  was appointed the [[Global Environment Facility]] Coordinator for MENA at [[UNDP]], where she oversaw the global environment portfolio in 22 Arab countries. <ref>{{cite book|title= Prof Wolf T., Aaron eds, ''Sharing Water, Sharing Benefits: Working towards effective transboundary water resources management''|url=https://books.google.com/?id=wJGMAgAAQBAJ&pg=PR12&lpg=PR12&dq=%22inger+andersen%22+%26+international+waters+partnership#v=onepage&q=%22inger%20andersen%22%20%26%20international%20waters%20partnership&f=false|isbn = 9789231041679|last1 = Wolf|first1 = Aaron T.|date = 2010-06-06}}</ref>\n\n===World Bank===\nAndersen joined the [[World Bank]] in 1999 as Coordinator of the UNDP-World Bank International Waters Partnership between 1999 and 2001 <ref>{{cite book|title= Prof Wolf T., Aaron eds, ''Sharing Water, Sharing Benefits: Working towards effective transboundary water resources management''|url=https://books.google.com/?id=wJGMAgAAQBAJ&pg=PR12&lpg=PR12&dq=%22inger+andersen%22+%26+international+waters+partnership#v=onepage&q=%22inger%20andersen%22%20%26%20international%20waters%20partnership&f=false|isbn = 9789231041679|last1 = Wolf|first1 = Aaron T.|date = 2010-06-06}}</ref> In the following years she worked in various roles, focussing on water, environment and sustainable development, with the Middle East and North Africa as her main area of work.  \n\nFrom 2010 until 2011, Andersen served as the World Bank\u2019s Vice President for Sustainable Development and Head of the [[CGIAR]] Fund Council <ref>{{cite web|title= Fund Council Chair Inger Andersen|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=B5KV8bSDS00|website=Youtube|access-date=13 July 2017}}</ref> <ref>{{cite web|title=Inger Andersen World Bank profile|url=http://blogs.worldbank.org/team/inger-andersen|website=World Bank|access-date=13 July 2017}}</ref>. During her tenure she oversaw the creation of the GCIAR Fund Council and the CG Consortium. <ref>{{cite web|title=Inger Andersen, Carlos Perez del Castillo and Bernard Hubert in Montpellier for the CGIAR Funders Forum|url=https://vimeo.com/22104513|access-date=13 July 2017|date=2011-04-08}}</ref> As Vice President for Sustainable Development, Andersen profiled a number of World Bank priorities, including: agricultural productivity and enhancing food security; <ref>{{cite web|title=2020 conf - Day 2 Dinner keynote - ;Inger Andersen|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=FxqF_kq9VZQ|website=Youtube|access-date=13 July 2017}}</ref> infrastructure investment; climate change resilience; <ref>{{cite web|title=Inger Andersen, World Bank VP for Sustainable Development at UN Climate Change Conference in Cancun|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=4iKwa8Dp5Do|website=Youtube|access-date=13 July 2017}}</ref> green growth; <ref>{{cite web|title='Green Growth and Development -- It's Possible'|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=UaDEW26ZeoA|website=Youtube|access-date=13 July 2017}}</ref> social accountability; disaster risk management; and culture and development. <ref>{{cite web|title=World Bank and UNESCO: Expanding Opportunities for Collaboration on Culture and Sustainable Development|url=https://whc.unesco.org/en/news/778/|website=UNESCO|access-date=13 July 2017}}</ref>\n\nDuring her tenure as Sector Director she oversaw the scaling-up of the World Bank\u2019s analytical and investment support to underpin resilient infrastructure development for access to energy, water and transport as well as investments in the agriculture and environment sectors. <ref>{{cite web|title= 'Africa's Energy Needs - Climate Change'|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=QEHr7gsprFI|website=Youtube|access-date=13 July 2017}}</ref> She placed special emphasis on the need to relieve climate and water stress in the region, both of which she argued pose key threats to peace and stability. <ref>{{cite web|title=More crop per drop in the Middle East and North Africa|url= http://blogs.worldbank.org/arabvoices/more-crop-drop-middle-east-and-north-africa|website=World Bank|access-date=13 July 2017}}</ref> <ref>{{cite web|title=World Bank: Arab World hit hard by climate change|url=https://www.usnews.com/news/world/articles/2012/12/05/world-bank-arab-world-hit-hard-by-climate-change|website=US News|access-date=13 July 2017}}</ref>\n\nAndersen co-chaired the 2012 international donor meeting for Yemen Riyadh with the then [[Ministry of Finance (Saudi Arabia)|Finance Minister]] of Saudi Arabia, [[Ibrahim Abdulaziz Al-Assaf]].<ref>{{cite web|title='Saudi Arabia's Finance Minister Ibrahim al-Assaf and President of the World Bank, Inger Andersen chair the international donor meeting for Yemen, in Riyadh on September 4, 2012'|url=http://www.gettyimages.ae/detail/news-photo/saudi-arabias-finance-minister-ibrahim-al-assaf-and-news-photo/151213292?#saudi-arabias-finance-minister-ibrahim-alassaf-and-president-of-the-picture-id151213292|website=gettyimages|access-date=13 July 2017}}</ref> As Vice President for MENA, Andersen was also outspoken on the humanitarian consequences of the war in Gaza in 2014, and called for access to imports and freedom of movement in Gaza and the West Bank, while stressing the imperative of mutual assurance of security in both Palestinian territories and Israel.<ref>{{cite web|title=What I saw in Gaza|url=http://www.aljazeera.com/indepth/opinion/2014/11/what-i-saw-gaza-20141149645737912.html|website=Al Jazeera|access-date=13 July 2017}}</ref>In 2011, Andersen represented the World Bank in the G8/G7 Finance Minister\u2019s Deauville meetings <ref>{{cite web|title=Partenariat de Deauville du G8 avec les pays arabes en transition|url=http://www.tresor.economie.gouv.fr/3865_partenariat-de-deauville-du-g8-avec-les-pays-arabes-en-transition|website=Tresor|access-date=13 July 2017}}</ref> which sought to provide additional support to the Arab Region. <ref>{{cite web|title=Panel Discussion on Arab Countries in Transition|url=https://vimeo.com/40090606|website=Vimeo|access-date=13 July 2017}}{{Dead link|date=January 2020 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\n===International Union for Conservation of Nature===\nAndersen was appointed Director General of the [[International Union for Conservation of Nature]] (IUCN) in January 2015. <ref>{{cite web|title=Inger Andersen named IUCN Director General|url=http://www.iucn.org/?18465/Inger-Andersen-named-IUCN-Director-General|website=IUCN|access-date=3 December 2014|date=2014-10-14}}</ref> <ref>{{cite web|title=World Bank loses top management for South Asia, MENA|url=https://www.devex.com/news/world-bank-loses-top-management-for-south-asia-mena-84576|website=Devex|access-date=13 July 2017|date=2014-10-17}}</ref> As Director General, Andersen was responsible for IUCN\u2019s operations in its 50 plus offices worldwide <ref>{{cite web|title=About IUCN|url=https://www.iucn.org/about|website=IUCN|access-date=13 July 2017}}</ref>\n\nUnder Andersen's leadership, IUCN held its 2016 World Conservation Congress in Hawaii, United States. The 2016 Congress was the largest international conservation event held in the United States. It was opened by President [[Barack Obama]] on the eve of the formal opening <ref>{{cite web|title=Obama: No Nation, Not Even One As Powerful As The U.S., Is Immune From Climate Change|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/entry/obama-hawaii-monument_us_57c7269de4b078581f10c56e|website=Huffington Post|access-date=13 July 2017|date=September 2016}}</ref> <ref>{{cite web|title=President Obama speaking at East-West Center|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=JtXD6-hfLpY|website=Youtube|access-date=13 July 2017}}</ref> \n\nDuring Andersen\u2019s tenure at IUCN she emphasized the importance of nature conservation in efforts to achieve sustainable development. \u201cNature is not an obstacle to human aspirations, but an essential partner, offering valuable contributions towards all our endeavours.\u201d <ref>{{cite news|title='Failing to protect nature's capital could cost businesses trillions'|url=https://www.theguardian.com/sustainable-business/2015/jan/28/natural-captial-profit-world-economy|newspaper=The Guardian|access-date=13 July 2017|date=2015-01-28|last1=Andersen|first1=Inger}}</ref> <ref>{{cite news|title=The natural way forward|url=https://www.theguardian.com/the-gef-partner-zone/2016/jul/29/the-natural-way-forward|newspaper=The Guardian|access-date=13 July 2017}}</ref>\n\n=== UNEP ===\nOn February 21 2019, the [[United Nations General Assembly|General Assembly of the United Nation]]<nowiki/>s elected Andersen as Executive Director of the [[United Nations Environment Programme]] (UNEP). She was appointed for a four-year term. <ref name=\":0\" /> \n\n==Other activities==\n===International organizations===\n* [[United Nations Global Compact]], Member of the Board<ref>{{cite web|title=UN Global Compact Board Members|url=https://www.unglobalcompact.org/about/governance/board/members}}</ref>\n* [[United Nations Environment Programme]] (UNEP), Member of the Financial Inquiry Advisory Committee\n===Corporate boards=== \n* [[Nespresso]], Member of the Sustainability Advisory Board (NSAB)<ref>{{cite web|title=Nespresso Sustainability Advisory Board|url=https://www.nestle-nespresso.com/sustainability/sustainability-advisory-board/board-members}}</ref>\n===Non-profit organizations===\n* Sustainable Development Solutions Network (SDSN), Member of the High-level Leadership Council<ref>{{cite web|title=SDSN High-level Leadership Council|url=http://unsdsn.org/about-us/leadership-council/|access-date=2017-07-13|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190707182824/http://unsdsn.org/about-us/leadership-council/|archive-date=2019-07-07|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n* [[Sustainable Energy for All]] (SE4All), Member of the Advisory Board <ref>{{cite web|title=SE4All Advisory Board members|url=http://www.se4all.org/about-us/advisory-board }}</ref> \n* The Economics of Ecosystems and Biodiversity ([[TEEB]]), Member of the Advisory Board <ref>{{cite web|title=TEEB Advisory Board members|url=http://www.teebweb.org/about/teeb-advisory/}}</ref> \n* [[World Economic Forum]] (WEF), Global Agenda Trustee for Environment and Natural Resource Security<ref>{{cite web|title= About: World Economic Forum's System Initiative on Shaping the Future of Environment and Natural Resource Securit|url= https://www.weforum.org/system-initiatives/environment-and-natural-resource-security}}</ref> \n* 2030 Water Resources Group, Member of the Governing Council and Steering Board<ref>{{cite web|title=UN Global Compact Board Members|url=https://www.2030wrg.org/who-we-are/governance/}}</ref> \n* Eco Forum Global, Member of the International Advisory Council (EFG-IAC)\n* [[International Olympic Committee]] (IOC), Member of the Sustainability and Legacy Commission<ref>[https://www.olympic.org/sustainability-and-legacy-commission Sustainability and Legacy Commission] [[International Olympic Committee]] (IOC).</ref>\n\n== Selected publications ==\n* Andersen, I., and George Golitzen, K.,  eds. [https://openknowledge.worldbank.org/handle/10986/11747 The Niger river basin: A vision for sustainable management]. World Bank Publications, 2005.\n* Prof Wolf T., Aaron eds, '[https://books.google.ch/books?id=wJGMAgAAQBAJ&pg=PR12&dq=sharing+water+sharing+benefits+%26+andersen&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwi03YTM2-jUAhVLBsAKHai_BLoQ6AEIJjAA#v=onepage&q=sharing%20water%20sharing%20benefits%20%26%20andersen&f=false Sharing Water, Sharing Benefits: Working towards effective transboundary water resources management: A graduate/professional skills-building workbook]', UNESCO Oregon State University. 2010.\n* Gladstone, W. et al. [http://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S096456919900040X?via%3Dihub Sustainable Use of Renewable Resources and Conservation in the Red Sea and Gulf of Aden], Elsevier, Vol 42. 1999. \n*Andersen, I. [https://impakter.com/healthy-oceans-sustainable-future/ Healthy Oceans: The Cornerstone for A Sustainable Future], Impakter.com. 2017<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://impakter.com/healthy-oceans-sustainable-future/|title=Healthy Oceans: The Cornerstone for A Sustainable Future|last=Inger|first=About the Author /|last2=ersen|date=2017-06-16|website=Impakter|language=en-US|access-date=2019-04-09}}</ref>\n\n==Honors and awards==\n* [[International Road Federation]] 2013 Professional of the Year <ref>{{cite web|title= IRF Annual Report. p.9|url= https://issuu.com/irfglobal/docs/2013-irf-annual-report}}</ref> \n* [[Tufts University]] Dr. Jean Mayer Award 2014 <ref>{{cite web|title= Mayer Award Recipients|url= http://www.tuftsgloballeadership.org/mayer-award-recipients?category=135}}</ref>\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [https://www.iucn.org/about/union/secretariat/director_general Inger Andersen], IUCN\n* [https://twitter.com/andersen_inger Inger Andersen] Twitter account\n\n{{Authority control}} \n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Andersen, Inger}}\n[[Category:1958 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Danish economists]]\n[[Category:Danish women economists]]\n[[Category:Danish environmentalists]]\n[[Category:Danish women environmentalists]]\n[[Category:Alumni of SOAS University of London]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the University of London]]\n[[Category:World Bank people]]\n[[Category:People associated with the International Union for Conservation of Nature]]\n[[Category:Danish officials of the United Nations]]\n[[Category:People from Frederikshavn Municipality]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox officeholder\n|name         = Inger Andersen\n|image        = Inger Andersen (environmentalist, 2010, cropped).jpg\n|office1       = Executive Director of the [[United Nations Environment Programme]] (UNEP)\n|term_start1   = TBD*\n|succeeding1   = [[Joyce Msuya]] {{small|(Acting)}}\n|office2       = Director General, [[International Union for Conservation of Nature]] (IUCN)\n|term_start2   = January 2015 \n|predecessor2  = [[Julia Marton-Lef\u00e8vre]]\n|nationality  = [[Denmark|Danish]]\n|birth_date   = 1958\n|birth_name   = Inger la Cour Andersen\n|birth_place  = [[Jerup]], Denmark\n|alma_mater   = [[London Metropolitan University]] and [[School of Oriental and African Studies]]\n|website      = [https://www.iucn.org/about/senior-management/director-general Official biography] }}\n\n'''Inger Andersen''' (born 23 May 1958) is a [[Denmark|Danish]] [[economist]] and [[environmentalist]]. In February 2019, she was appointed as the Executive Director of the [[United Nations Environment Programme]] [[UNEP]]. <ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.unenvironment.org/news-and-stories/press-release/un-secretary-general-appoints-inger-andersen-denmark-executive|title=UN Secretary-General appoints Inger Andersen of Denmark as Executive Director of the UN Environment|website=UN Environment|language=en|access-date=2019-04-21}}</ref> \n\nPrior to her appointment, at UNEP, Andersen was Director General of the [[International Union for Conservation of Nature]] (IUCN),<ref>{{cite web|title=Inger Andersen named IUCN Director General|url=http://www.iucn.org/?18465/Inger-Andersen-named-IUCN-Director-General|website=IUCN|access-date=3 December 2014|date=2014-10-14}}</ref> Vice President for Sustainable Development at the [[World Bank]] and Head of the [[CGIAR]] Fund Council and then World Bank Vice President for the Middle East and North Africa <ref>{{cite web|title=Inger Andersen World Bank profile|url=http://blogs.worldbank.org/team/inger-andersen|website=World Bank|access-date=13 July 2017}}</ref> \n\n== Family, early life and education ==\nInger Andersen is the daughter of Aagot la Cour Andersen and Erik Andersen.<ref>{{cite web|title=69: Lyngby-Linienhttp|url=http://www.pierrelacour.dk/s-bog/69-lyngby.htm|accessdate=13 July 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20050525232335/http://pierrelacour.dk/s-bog/69-lyngby.htm|archive-date=25 May 2005|url-status=dead}}</ref> She is the granddaughter of Danish historian and archaeologist Vilhelm la Cour. Her brother was Hans la Cour, author and film maker, known in the world of sail sport <ref>{{cite web|title=Eight Bells ... Hans La Cour Andersen|url=http://www.sail-world.com/Australia/Eight-Bells--Hans-La-Cour-Andersen/62776?source=google.ch|website=Sail-World|access-date=13 July 2017}}</ref> and environmental documentaries. <ref>{{cite web|title=Hans la Cour|url=https://www.imdb.com/name/nm1750616/?ref_=tt_ov_dr|website=IMDb|access-date=13 July 2017}}</ref>\n \nAndersen was born in [[Jerup]], Denmark. She graduated from Midtfyns Gymnasium secondary school in 1977. Andersen obtained a BA in 1981 from the Polytechnic of North London (now [[London Metropolitan University]]) and in 1982 gained an MA degree from the [[School of Oriental and African Studies]] at [[University of London]], with a specialisation in development studies focusing on economics and development. <ref>{{cite web|title=World Bank experts: Inger Andersen|url=http://live.worldbank.org/experts/inger-andersen|website=World Bank|access-date=3 December 2014|date=2013-08-12}}</ref>\n\n== Career ==\nAndersen started her career in Sudan in 1982 where she worked initially as an English teacher under the UK funded English teachers programme. In 1985 she joined SudanAid, the development and relief arm of the [[Sudan Catholic Bishops' Conference]]. Her work focused on famine and drought relief, and rehabilitation. <ref>{{cite web|title=69: Lyngby-Linienhttp|url=http://www.pierrelacour.dk/s-bog/69-lyngby.htm|accessdate=13 July 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20050525232335/http://pierrelacour.dk/s-bog/69-lyngby.htm|archive-date=25 May 2005|url-status=dead}}</ref> <ref>{{cite web|title= Inger Andersen - \"We must continue work towards fairer and more sustainable world\"|url=http://sustainability.thomsonreuters.com/women/inger-andersen-must-continue-work-towards-fairer-sustainable-world/|website=Thomson Reuters|access-date=14 July 2017|date=2017-06-14}}</ref> <ref>{{cite web|title= World Bank names three new vice presidents at the End of its Biggest Lending Year Ever|url=http://www.worldbank.org/en/news/press-release/2010/07/01/world-bank-names-three-new-vice-presidents-end-biggest-lending-year-ever|website=World Bank|access-date=13 July 2017}}</ref>\n\n===United Nations===\nAndersen worked at the [[United Nations]] in New York for 12 years at the UN Sudano-Sahelian Office (UNSO), (now the Global Policy Centre on Resilient Ecosystems and Desertification based in Nairobi<ref>{{cite web|title=Global Policy Centre on Resilient Ecosystems and Desertification|url=http://www.undp.org/content/undp/en/home/ourwork/global-policy-centres/sustainable_landmanagement/integrated_drylandsdevelopmentprogramme.html|accessdate=13 July 2017}}</ref>) where she worked on drought and [[desertification]] issues. In 1992, she  was appointed the [[Global Environment Facility]] Coordinator for MENA at [[UNDP]], where she oversaw the global environment portfolio in 22 Arab countries. <ref>{{cite book|title= Prof Wolf T., Aaron eds, ''Sharing Water, Sharing Benefits: Working towards effective transboundary water resources management''|url=https://books.google.com/?id=wJGMAgAAQBAJ&pg=PR12&lpg=PR12&dq=%22inger+andersen%22+%26+international+waters+partnership#v=onepage&q=%22inger%20andersen%22%20%26%20international%20waters%20partnership&f=false|isbn = 9789231041679|last1 = Wolf|first1 = Aaron T.|date = 2010-06-06}}</ref>\n\n===World Bank===\nAndersen joined the [[World Bank]] in 1999 as Coordinator of the UNDP-World Bank International Waters Partnership between 1999 and 2001 <ref>{{cite book|title= Prof Wolf T., Aaron eds, ''Sharing Water, Sharing Benefits: Working towards effective transboundary water resources management''|url=https://books.google.com/?id=wJGMAgAAQBAJ&pg=PR12&lpg=PR12&dq=%22inger+andersen%22+%26+international+waters+partnership#v=onepage&q=%22inger%20andersen%22%20%26%20international%20waters%20partnership&f=false|isbn = 9789231041679|last1 = Wolf|first1 = Aaron T.|date = 2010-06-06}}</ref> In the following years she worked in various roles, focussing on water, environment and sustainable development, with the Middle East and North Africa as her main area of work.  \n\nFrom 2010 until 2011, Andersen served as the World Bank\u2019s Vice President for Sustainable Development and Head of the [[CGIAR]] Fund Council <ref>{{cite web|title= Fund Council Chair Inger Andersen|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=B5KV8bSDS00|website=Youtube|access-date=13 July 2017}}</ref> <ref>{{cite web|title=Inger Andersen World Bank profile|url=http://blogs.worldbank.org/team/inger-andersen|website=World Bank|access-date=13 July 2017}}</ref>. During her tenure she oversaw the creation of the GCIAR Fund Council and the CG Consortium. <ref>{{cite web|title=Inger Andersen, Carlos Perez del Castillo and Bernard Hubert in Montpellier for the CGIAR Funders Forum|url=https://vimeo.com/22104513|access-date=13 July 2017|date=2011-04-08}}</ref> As Vice President for Sustainable Development, Andersen profiled a number of World Bank priorities, including: agricultural productivity and enhancing food security; <ref>{{cite web|title=2020 conf - Day 2 Dinner keynote - ;Inger Andersen|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=FxqF_kq9VZQ|website=Youtube|access-date=13 July 2017}}</ref> infrastructure investment; climate change resilience; <ref>{{cite web|title=Inger Andersen, World Bank VP for Sustainable Development at UN Climate Change Conference in Cancun|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=4iKwa8Dp5Do|website=Youtube|access-date=13 July 2017}}</ref> green growth; <ref>{{cite web|title='Green Growth and Development -- It's Possible'|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=UaDEW26ZeoA|website=Youtube|access-date=13 July 2017}}</ref> social accountability; disaster risk management; and culture and development. <ref>{{cite web|title=World Bank and UNESCO: Expanding Opportunities for Collaboration on Culture and Sustainable Development|url=https://whc.unesco.org/en/news/778/|website=UNESCO|access-date=13 July 2017}}</ref>\n\nDuring her tenure as Sector Director she oversaw the scaling-up of the World Bank\u2019s analytical and investment support to underpin resilient infrastructure development for access to energy, water and transport as well as investments in the agriculture and environment sectors. <ref>{{cite web|title= 'Africa's Energy Needs - Climate Change'|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=QEHr7gsprFI|website=Youtube|access-date=13 July 2017}}</ref> She placed special emphasis on the need to relieve climate and water stress in the region, both of which she argued pose key threats to peace and stability. <ref>{{cite web|title=More crop per drop in the Middle East and North Africa|url= http://blogs.worldbank.org/arabvoices/more-crop-drop-middle-east-and-north-africa|website=World Bank|access-date=13 July 2017}}</ref> <ref>{{cite web|title=World Bank: Arab World hit hard by climate change|url=https://www.usnews.com/news/world/articles/2012/12/05/world-bank-arab-world-hit-hard-by-climate-change|website=US News|access-date=13 July 2017}}</ref>\n\nAndersen co-chaired the 2012 international donor meeting for Yemen Riyadh with the then [[Ministry of Finance (Saudi Arabia)|Finance Minister]] of Saudi Arabia, [[Ibrahim Abdulaziz Al-Assaf]].<ref>{{cite web|title='Saudi Arabia's Finance Minister Ibrahim al-Assaf and President of the World Bank, Inger Andersen chair the international donor meeting for Yemen, in Riyadh on September 4, 2012'|url=http://www.gettyimages.ae/detail/news-photo/saudi-arabias-finance-minister-ibrahim-al-assaf-and-news-photo/151213292?#saudi-arabias-finance-minister-ibrahim-alassaf-and-president-of-the-picture-id151213292|website=gettyimages|access-date=13 July 2017}}</ref> As Vice President for MENA, Andersen was also outspoken on the humanitarian consequences of the war in Gaza in 2014, and called for access to imports and freedom of movement in Gaza and the West Bank, while stressing the imperative of mutual assurance of security in both Palestinian territories and Israel.<ref>{{cite web|title=What I saw in Gaza|url=http://www.aljazeera.com/indepth/opinion/2014/11/what-i-saw-gaza-20141149645737912.html|website=Al Jazeera|access-date=13 July 2017}}</ref>In 2011, Andersen represented the World Bank in the G8/G7 Finance Minister\u2019s Deauville meetings <ref>{{cite web|title=Partenariat de Deauville du G8 avec les pays arabes en transition|url=http://www.tresor.economie.gouv.fr/3865_partenariat-de-deauville-du-g8-avec-les-pays-arabes-en-transition|website=Tresor|access-date=13 July 2017}}</ref> which sought to provide additional support to the Arab Region. <ref>{{cite web|title=Panel Discussion on Arab Countries in Transition|url=https://vimeo.com/40090606|website=Vimeo|access-date=13 July 2017}}{{Dead link|date=January 2020 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\n===International Union for Conservation of Nature===\nAndersen was appointed Director General of the [[International Union for Conservation of Nature]] (IUCN) in January 2015. <ref>{{cite web|title=Inger Andersen named IUCN Director General|url=http://www.iucn.org/?18465/Inger-Andersen-named-IUCN-Director-General|website=IUCN|access-date=3 December 2014|date=2014-10-14}}</ref> <ref>{{cite web|title=World Bank loses top management for South Asia, MENA|url=https://www.devex.com/news/world-bank-loses-top-management-for-south-asia-mena-84576|website=Devex|access-date=13 July 2017|date=2014-10-17}}</ref> As Director General, Andersen was responsible for IUCN\u2019s operations in its 50 plus offices worldwide <ref>{{cite web|title=About IUCN|url=https://www.iucn.org/about|website=IUCN|access-date=13 July 2017}}</ref>\n\nUnder Andersen's leadership, IUCN held its 2016 World Conservation Congress in Hawaii, United States. The 2016 Congress was the largest international conservation event held in the United States. It was opened by President [[Barack Obama]] on the eve of the formal opening <ref>{{cite web|title=Obama: No Nation, Not Even One As Powerful As The U.S., Is Immune From Climate Change|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/entry/obama-hawaii-monument_us_57c7269de4b078581f10c56e|website=Huffington Post|access-date=13 July 2017|date=September 2016}}</ref> <ref>{{cite web|title=President Obama speaking at East-West Center|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=JtXD6-hfLpY|website=Youtube|access-date=13 July 2017}}</ref> \n\nDuring Andersen\u2019s tenure at IUCN she emphasized the importance of nature conservation in efforts to achieve sustainable development. \u201cNature is not an obstacle to human aspirations, but an essential partner, offering valuable contributions towards all our endeavours.\u201d <ref>{{cite news|title='Failing to protect nature's capital could cost businesses trillions'|url=https://www.theguardian.com/sustainable-business/2015/jan/28/natural-captial-profit-world-economy|newspaper=The Guardian|access-date=13 July 2017|date=2015-01-28|last1=Andersen|first1=Inger}}</ref> <ref>{{cite news|title=The natural way forward|url=https://www.theguardian.com/the-gef-partner-zone/2016/jul/29/the-natural-way-forward|newspaper=The Guardian|access-date=13 July 2017}}</ref>\n\n=== UNEP ===\nOn February 21 2019, the [[United Nations General Assembly|General Assembly of the United Nation]]<nowiki/>s elected Andersen as Executive Director of the [[United Nations Environment Programme]] (UNEP). She was appointed for a four-year term. <ref name=\":0\" /> \n\n==Other activities==\n===International organizations===\n* [[United Nations Global Compact]], Member of the Board<ref>{{cite web|title=UN Global Compact Board Members|url=https://www.unglobalcompact.org/about/governance/board/members}}</ref>\n* [[United Nations Environment Programme]] (UNEP), Member of the Financial Inquiry Advisory Committee\n===Corporate boards=== \n* [[Nespresso]], Member of the Sustainability Advisory Board (NSAB)<ref>{{cite web|title=Nespresso Sustainability Advisory Board|url=https://www.nestle-nespresso.com/sustainability/sustainability-advisory-board/board-members}}</ref>\n===Non-profit organizations===\n* Sustainable Development Solutions Network (SDSN), Member of the High-level Leadership Council<ref>{{cite web|title=SDSN High-level Leadership Council|url=http://unsdsn.org/about-us/leadership-council/|access-date=2017-07-13|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190707182824/http://unsdsn.org/about-us/leadership-council/|archive-date=2019-07-07|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n* [[Sustainable Energy for All]] (SE4All), Member of the Advisory Board <ref>{{cite web|title=SE4All Advisory Board members|url=http://www.se4all.org/about-us/advisory-board }}</ref> \n* The Economics of Ecosystems and Biodiversity ([[TEEB]]), Member of the Advisory Board <ref>{{cite web|title=TEEB Advisory Board members|url=http://www.teebweb.org/about/teeb-advisory/}}</ref> \n* [[World Economic Forum]] (WEF), Global Agenda Trustee for Environment and Natural Resource Security<ref>{{cite web|title= About: World Economic Forum's System Initiative on Shaping the Future of Environment and Natural Resource Securit|url= https://www.weforum.org/system-initiatives/environment-and-natural-resource-security}}</ref> \n* 2030 Water Resources Group, Member of the Governing Council and Steering Board<ref>{{cite web|title=UN Global Compact Board Members|url=https://www.2030wrg.org/who-we-are/governance/}}</ref> \n* Eco Forum Global, Member of the International Advisory Council (EFG-IAC)\n* [[International Olympic Committee]] (IOC), Member of the Sustainability and Legacy Commission<ref>[https://www.olympic.org/sustainability-and-legacy-commission Sustainability and Legacy Commission] [[International Olympic Committee]] (IOC).</ref>\n\n== Selected publications ==\n* Andersen, I., and George Golitzen, K.,  eds. [https://openknowledge.worldbank.org/handle/10986/11747 The Niger river basin: A vision for sustainable management]. World Bank Publications, 2005.\n* Prof Wolf T., Aaron eds, '[https://books.google.ch/books?id=wJGMAgAAQBAJ&pg=PR12&dq=sharing+water+sharing+benefits+%26+andersen&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwi03YTM2-jUAhVLBsAKHai_BLoQ6AEIJjAA#v=onepage&q=sharing%20water%20sharing%20benefits%20%26%20andersen&f=false Sharing Water, Sharing Benefits: Working towards effective transboundary water resources management: A graduate/professional skills-building workbook]', UNESCO Oregon State University. 2010.\n* Gladstone, W. et al. [http://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S096456919900040X?via%3Dihub Sustainable Use of Renewable Resources and Conservation in the Red Sea and Gulf of Aden], Elsevier, Vol 42. 1999. \n*Andersen, I. [https://impakter.com/healthy-oceans-sustainable-future/ Healthy Oceans: The Cornerstone for A Sustainable Future], Impakter.com. 2017<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://impakter.com/healthy-oceans-sustainable-future/|title=Healthy Oceans: The Cornerstone for A Sustainable Future|last=Inger|first=About the Author /|last2=ersen|date=2017-06-16|website=Impakter|language=en-US|access-date=2019-04-09}}</ref>\n\n==Honors and awards==\n* [[International Road Federation]] 2013 Professional of the Year <ref>{{cite web|title= IRF Annual Report. p.9|url= https://issuu.com/irfglobal/docs/2013-irf-annual-report}}</ref> \n* [[Tufts University]] Dr. Jean Mayer Award 2014 <ref>{{cite web|title= Mayer Award Recipients|url= http://www.tuftsgloballeadership.org/mayer-award-recipients?category=135}}</ref>\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [https://www.iucn.org/about/union/secretariat/director_general Inger Andersen], IUCN\n* [https://twitter.com/andersen_inger Inger Andersen] Twitter account\n\n{{Authority control}} \n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Andersen, Inger}}\n[[Category:1958 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Danish economists]]\n[[Category:Danish women economists]]\n[[Category:Danish environmentalists]]\n[[Category:Danish women environmentalists]]\n[[Category:Alumni of SOAS University of London]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the University of London]]\n[[Category:World Bank people]]\n[[Category:People associated with the International Union for Conservation of Nature]]\n[[Category:Danish officials of the United Nations]]\n", "name_user": "ArbieP", "label": "safe", "comment": "addedCategory:People from Frederikshavn Municipality", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Inger_Andersen_(environmentalist)"}
{"title_page": "Lois Lowry", "text_new": "{{Short description|American writer}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=October 2012}}\n{{Infobox writer <!-- for more information see [[:Template:Infobox writer/doc]] -->\n| name = Lois Lowry\n| image = Lois Lowry 2016.jpg\n| imagesize = \n| caption = Lowry at the 2016 [[Texas Book Festival]]\n| birth_name = Lois Ann Hammersberg<ref name=\"Biography\">{{cite web |title=Lois Lowry |url=https://www.biography.com/people/lois-lowry |website=Biography |accessdate=14 April 2019}}</ref>\n| birth_date = {{Birth date and age|1937|3|20}}\n| birth_place = [[Honolulu]], [[Hawaii]], U.S.\n| death_date = \n| death_place = \n| occupation = Writer\n| period = 1977\u2013present\n| genre = Children's literature, [[fantasy]]\n| movement = \n| spouse = Donald Grey Lowry (1956-1977; divorced; 4 children, 2 sons and 2 daughters)\n| residence = [[Massachusetts]], U.S.<br/>[[Maine]], U.S.\n| notableworks = {{plainlist|\n* ''[[The Giver]]''\n* ''[[Number the Stars]]''}}\n| awards = {{awd |[[Newbery Medal]] |1990, 1994}} {{awd |[[Margaret Edwards Award]] |2007}}\n| website = {{URL|loislowry.com/}}\n}}\n'''Lois Lowry''' (born '''Lois Ann Hammersberg''' on March 20, 1937) is an American writer. She is the author of several books for children and young adults, including ''[[The Giver Quartet]]'' and ''[[Number the Stars]]''. She is known for writing about difficult subject matters and complex themes in works for young audiences. \n\nLowry has won two [[Newbery Medal]]s: for ''[[Number the Stars]]'' in 1990 and ''[[The Giver]]'' in 1994.<ref name=\"newbery\" />  Her book ''[[Gooney Bird Greene]]'' won the 2002 Rhode Island Children's Book Award.\n\n==Personal life==\nLowry was born on March 20, 1937, in [[Honolulu]], [[Hawaii]],<ref name=pabook/> to parents Katherine Gordon Landis and Robert E. Hammersberg. Initially, Lowry's parents named her \"Cena\"  for her Norwegian grandmohearing this, her grandmother [[telegram|telegraphed]] and instructed Lowry's parents that the child should have an American name.<ref>[http://www.loislowry.com/pdf/Richmond_Speech.pdf Lois Lowry<!-- Bot generated title -->] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.orgl. Lowry and her family briefly lived in Carlisle again in 1950 before moving to [[Governors Island]], New York, where Lowry attended [[Curtis High School]] on [[Staten Island]]. She began attending [[Packer Collegiate Institute]] in [[Brooklyn Heights]], New York, in 1952, and graduated in 1954 before\nLowry continued at the school for two years, departing after her marriage to Donald Grey Lowry, a [[U.S. Navy]] officer, in 1956.<ref name=\"autogenerated2\" /> Together, they had four children: daughters Alix and Kristin, and sons Grey and Benjamin.<ref name=\"autogenerated2\">[http://www.pabook.libraries.psu.edu/LitMap/bios/Lowry_Lois.html Lowry, Lois<!-- Bot generated title -->] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071110001725/http://www.pabook.libraries.psu.edu/LitMap/bios/Lowry_Lois.html |date=November 10, 2007 }}</ref>\n\nWhile raising her children, Lowry completed her degree in English literature at the [[University of Southern Maine]]<ref name=\"loislowry.com\">[http://www.loislowry.com/bio.html Lois Lowry<!-- Bot generated title -->] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160128115700/http://www.loislowry.com/bio.html |date=January 28, 2016 }}</ref> in Portland in 1972. After earning her B.A., she continued at the school to pursue graduate studies.\n\nIn 1977, at the age of 40, Lowry's first book, \"[[A Summer to Die]]\", was published. She and Donald Lowry divorced that same year.<ref name=\"autogenerated2\" />\n\nLowry's son Grey, a USAF major, was killed in the crash of his fighter plane in 1995.<ref>{{cite news|last=Kois|first=Dan|title=The Children's Author Who Actually Listens to Children|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2012/10/07/magazine/lois-lowry-the-childrens-author-who-actually-listens-to-children.html?_r=0|accessdate=5 March 2014|newspaper=New York Times|date=October 3, 2012}}</ref> Lowry has acknowledged that this was the most difficult day of her life, and of his death she has said, \"His death in the cockpit of a warplane tore away a piece of my world. But it left me, too, with a wish to honor him by joining the many others trying to find a way to end conflict on this very fragile earth.\"<ref name=\"autogenerated1\" />\n\nToday, Lois Lowry has homes in both Massachusetts and Maine and remains an active writer and speaker.<ref name=\"autogenerated2\" />\n\n==Writing career==\n[[File:Lois lowry 0001.jpg|thumbnail|left|Lois Lowry at an event for the [[The Giver (film)|film adaption of ''The Giver'']] in 2014]]\n\nLowry began her career as a freelance journalist. In the 1970s, she submitted a short story to ''[[Redbook]]'' magazine, which was intended for adult audiences but written from a child's perspective.<ref name=\"autogenerated2\" /> An editor at [[Houghton Mifflin]] then suggested to Lowry that she write a children's book.<ref name=\"autogenerated2\" /> Lowry agreed and wrote ''[[A Summer to Die]]'' which Houghton Mifflin published in 1977 when she was 40 years old. The book has themes of [[terminal illness]], based on Lowry's own experiences with her sister Helen.<ref name=\"autogenerated2\" /> Lowry continued to write about difficult topics in her next publication, ''[[Autumn Street]]'' (1979), which explores themes of coping with [[racism]], [[grief]], and [[fear]] at a young age.<ref name=\"autogenerated2\" /> The novel is told from the perspective of a young girl who is sent to live with her grandfather during [[World War II]], based on by Lowry's own experiences during the war.<ref name=\"Biography\" />\nThe same year she published ''[[Autumn Street]]'', Lowry also published her novel ''[[Anastasia Krupnik]]'', the first installment in the Anastasia series.<ref name=\"Biography\" /> The series continued until 1995.\n\nLowry's work ''[[Number the Stars]]'' was published in 1989 and received multiple awards, including the 1990 Newbery medal.<ref name=\"newbery\" /> Lowry received the Newbery medal again in 1994, for ''[[The Giver]]'' (1993).<ref name=\"newbery\" /> After writing ''[[The Giver]]'', she published two companion novels which take place in the same universe: ''[[Gathering Blue]]'' (2000) and ''[[Messenger (novel)|Messenger]]'' (2004). In 2012, she published ''[[Son (novel)|Son]]'', which tied all three of the previous books together. As a set, they are considered ''[[The Giver Quartet]]''.<ref name=\"Biography\" />\n===Critical reception===\nIn her works, Lowry has explored such complex issues as [[racism]], [[terminal ilness]], [[murder]], [[the Holocaust]], and the questioning of [[authority]], among other challenging topics. Her writing on such matters has brought her both praise and criticism. In particular, ''[[The Giver]]'' (the first novel in the Quartet) has been met with a diversity of reactions from [[American schools|schools in America]] since its release in 1993; some schools have adopted it as a part of the mandatory curriculum, while others have prohibited the book's inclusion in classroom studies.{{citation needed|date=March 2020}}\n\n== Awards ==\nLowry won the [[Newbery Medal]] in 1990 for her novel ''[[Number the Stars]]'', and again in 1994 for ''[[The Giver]]''.<ref name=newbery/> For ''[[Number the Stars]]'', Lowry has also received the [[National Jewish -jewish-book-awards/past-winners|title=Past Winners|website=Jewish Book Council|language=en|access-date=2020-01-19}}</ref>, and the [[Dorothy Canfield Fisher Children's Book Award]] \nIn 1994, Lowry was awarded the [[Regina Medal]].{{citation needed|date=March 2020}}\n\nIn 2002, her book ''[[Gooney Bird Greene]]'' won the Rhode Island Children's Book [https://guides.rilinkschools.org/c.php?g=269052&p=1794336 Award.]{{citation needed|date=March 2020}}\n\nLowry has been nominated three times for the biennial internatal [[Hans Christian Andersen Award]], the highes recognition available to creators of children's books.<ref name=\"ibby2004\" /><ref name=\"ibby-no\" />  She was a finalist in 2000, a U.S. nominee in 2004, and analist in 2016.{{citation needed|date=March 2020}} \n\nIn 2007, she received the [[Margaret Edwards Award]] from the [[American Library Association]] for r contributions writing for teens.<ref name=\"edwards\" /> The ALA [[Margaret Edwards Award]] recognizes one writer and a particular body of work for \"significant and lasting contribution to young adult literature\".{{citation needed|date=March 2020}} Lowry won the annual award in 2007 for ''The Giver'' (published 1993). e citation observed that \"''The Giver'' was one of the most frequently challenged books from 1990\u20132000\" \u2014 that is, the object of \"a formal, written attempt to remove a book from a library or classroom.\" According to the panel chair, \"The book has held a unique position in teen literature. Lowry's exceptional use of metaphors and subtle complexity make it a book that will be discussed, debated and challenged for years to come...a perfect teen read.\"<ref name=edwards/>\n\nIn 2011 she gave the [[May Hill Arbuthnot Lecture]]; her lecture was titled \"UNLEAVING: The Sng Power of Gold\".<ref name=\"slcl.org\">{{cite web|url=http://www.slcl.org/content/slcl-host-2011-arbuthnot-lecture-lois-lowry|title=SLCL to Host 2011 Arbuthnot Lecture with Lois Lowry - St. Louis County Library|publisher=|accessdate=October 11, 2014}}</ref> She was also awarded an honorary [[Doctorate of Letters]] by [[Brown University]] in 2014.<ref name=\"brown\">{{cite web|title=Brown confers nine honorary degrees|url=http://news.brown.edu/pressreleases/2014/05/hdcitations#Lowry|publisher=Brown University|accessdate=27 May 2014|date=25 May 2014}}</ref>\n<ref name=\"Pina\">{{cite web|last=Pina|first=Alisha|title=Brown graduates told to question authority, challenge labels|url=http://www.providencejournal.com/breaking-news/content/20140525-brown-graduates-told-to-question-authority-challenge-labels.ece|per\u201d}}</ref> In addition, she holds honorary degrees from The [[University of Southern Maine]], [[Elmhurst College]], Wilson College, St. Mary's College, and [[Lesley University]].{{citation needed|date=March 2020}}\n\n==Works==\n\n{{Col-begin}}\n{{Col-break}}\n\n===Children's book series===\n\n;''[[The Giver Quartet]]''{{efn|name=giver}}\n* ''[[The Giver]]'' (1993)\n* ''[[Gathering Blue]]'' (2000)\n* ''[[Messenger (novel)|Messenger]]'' (2004)\n* ''[[Son (novel)|Son]]'' (2012)\n\n;Anastasia\n* ''[[Anastasia Krupnik]]'' (1979)\n* ''[[Anastasia Again!]]'' (1981)\n* ''[[Anastasia at Your Service]]'' (1982)\n* ''[[Anastasia, Ask Your Analyst]]'' (1984)\n* ''[[Anastasia on Her Own]]'' (1985)\n* ''[[Anastasia Has the Answers]]'' (1986)\n* ''[[Anastasia's Chosen Career]]'' (1987)\n* ''[[Anastasia at This Address]]'' (1991)\n* ''[[Anastasia Absolutely]]'' (1995)\n\n;Sam Krupnik\n* ''[[All about Sam]]'' (1988)\n* ''[[Attaboy Sam!]]'' (1992)\n* ''[[See You Around, Sam!]]'' (1996)\n* ''[[Zooman Sam]]'' (1999)\n\n{{anchor|The Tates Series}}\n;Tate Family\n* ''[[The One Hundredth Thing About Caroline]]'' (1983)\n* ''[[Switcharound]]'' (1985)\n* ''[[Your Move, J.P.!]]'' (1990)<ref>{{cite journal|last=Rosen|first=Martha, Luann Toth, and Virginia M. J. Suhr|title=Your Move, J.P.! (book)|journal=School Library Journal|date=May 1990|volume=36|issue=5|page=107}}</ref>\n\n;''Gooney Bird''\n* ''[[Gooney Bird Greene]]'' (2002)\n* ''[[Gooney Bird and the Room Mother]]'' (2006)\n* ''[[Gooney the Fabulous]]'' (2007)\n* ''[[Gooney Bird Is So Absurd]]'' (2009)\n* ''[[Gooney Bird on the Map]]'' (2011)\n* ''[[Gooney Bird and All Her Charms]]'' (2014)\n\n{{Col-break}}\n\n===Memoir===\n\n* ''[[Looking Back (book)|Looking Back]]'' (1998; expanded edition 2016)\n\n===Novels===\n* ''[[A Summer to Die]]'' (1977)\n* ''[[Find a Stranger, Say Goodbye]]'' (1978)\n* ''[[Autumn Street]]'' (1980)\n* ''[[Taking Care of Terrific]]'' (1983)\n* ''[[Us and Uncle Fraud]]'' (1984)\n* ''[[Rabble Starkey]]'' (1987)\n* ''[[Number the Stars]]'' (1989)\n* ''[[The Big Book for Peace]]'' (1990) (Illustrated by [[Trina Schart Hyman]])\n* ''[[Stay! Keeper's Story]]'' (1997)\n* ''[[The Silent Boy]]'' (2003)\n* ''[[Gossamer (novel)|Gossamer]]'' (2006)\n* ''[[The Willoughbys]]'' (2008)\n* ''[[Crow Call]]'' (2009)\n* ''[[The Birthday Ball]]'' (2010)\n* ''[[Bless This Mouse]]'' (2011)\n* ''[[Like the Willow Tree]]'' (2011)\n\n===Other===\n* ''[[Here in Kennebunkport]]'' (1978)\n{{col-end}}\n\n==Adaptations==\n*''[[The Giver (film)|The Giver]]'' (2014), film directed by [[Phillip Noyce]], based on young adult novel ''[[The Giver]]''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.movieinsider.com/m1036/the-giver/|title=The Giver|work=Movie Insider|accessdate=October 11, 2014}}</ref>\n==Notes==\n{{notelist |notes=\n{{efn |name=giver |1=\nWith the release of ''[[Son (novel)|Son]]'' (2012), the ''Giver'' series has been redefined as a finished \"quartet\" of fantasy novels. While ''[[Gathering Blue]]'' (2000) and ''[[Messenger (novel)|Messenger]]'' (2004) were only loosely related companions to ''[[The Giver]]'' (1993), ''Son'' ties all three storylines together, with \"heroes and fates colliding in a final, epic struggle.\"<br/>\n\u2022 {{Cite journal |last=Wasserman |first=Robin |authorlink=Robin Wasserman |date=14 October 2012 |title=The Searcher |journal=[[The New York Times Book Review]] |publisher=[[The New York Times Co.]] |page=1 |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2012/10/14/books/review/son-by-lois-lowry.html |accessdate=2012-11-02 }}\n}}\n}}\n\n== See also ==\n*[[Merkel Landis]], grandfather - started the Christmas Savings Club\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em|refs=\n\n<ref name=pabook>\n[http://pabook.libraries.psu.edu/palitmap/bios/Lowry_Lois.html \"Lois Lowry\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080311103355/http://pabook.libraries.psu.edu/palitmap/bios/Lowry_Lois.html |date=March 11, 2008 }}. Pennsylvania Center for the Book. Penn State University.</ref>\n\n<!