{"title_page": "2017 in radio", "text_new": "{{Globalize|article|the United States|date=January 2018}}\n{{Year nav topic5|2017|radio|music|television|home video}}\nThe following is a list of events affecting [[radio broadcasting]] in '''2017'''. Events listed include radio program debuts, finales, cancellations, and station launches, closures and format changes, as well as information about controversies.\n\n==Notable events==\n\n===January===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Date\n! Event\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|'''1'''\n|After a nearly two-year run with Active Rock, [[WBGF]] [[Belle Glade, Florida]]/[[West Palm Beach, Florida|West Palm Beach]] flipped to Oldies, a move that also ends its affiliation with [[Bubba the Love Sponge]]'s syndicated morning program in the market.<ref>[https://radioinsight.com/headlines/110030/west-palm-beachs-bar-gives-way-to-true-oldies/ \"West Palm Beach's Bar Gives Way To True Oldies\"] from ''Radio Insight'' (January 1, 2017)</ref>\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:center;\" rowspan=2|'''2'''\n|[[KWDO|KJWL]] [[Fresno, California|Fresno]] makes the flip to Top 40/CHR, filling the void that has been left open for nearly 10 years as well as new competition for Rhythmic rivals [[KBOS-FM]] and [[KSEQ]]. KJWL's Adult Album Alternative format adjusts to Soft AC and moves over to sister station [[KJWL|KJZN]], effectively dropping their Classic Hip-Hop format after nearly two years.<ref>[https://radioinsight.com/headlines/110041/99-3-now-fm-fresno-launches-as-jewel-fm-moves/ \"Now FM Launches As Jewel FM Moves\"] from ''Radio Insight'' (January 2, 2017)</ref>\n|-\n|After a six-month run with Dance/Rhythmic Top 40, only to see its sale to new owners fall through due to financial problems, [[WYKB|WZDJ]] [[Fernandina Beach, Florida]]/[[Jacksonville, Florida|Jacksonville]] flips to Country under the original ownership for the time being.<ref>[https://radioinsight.com/headlines/110054/105-3-jacksonville-sale-collapses-flips-to-country/ \"105.3 Jacksonville Sale Collapses; Flips To Country\"] from ''Radio Insight'' (January 2, 2017)</ref>\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|'''3'''\n|[[Entercom]] splits up the Active Rock simulcast of [[Boston]]'s [[WKVB (FM)|WAAF]] [[Westborough, Massachusetts]] and [[WKAF]] [[Brockton, Massachusetts]], with the latter flipping to [[Urban AC]] as \"The New 97.7\", returning the format to the market for the first time since 2006, when Entercom bought then-WILD-FM from [[Radio One, Inc.|Radio One]] and flipped it to the WAAF simulcast.<ref>[https://radioinsight.com/headlines/110083/format-change-imminent-at-97-7-wkaf-boston/ \"Format Change Imminent At 97.7 WKAF Boston\"] from ''Radio Insight'' (January 3, 2017)</ref>\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:center;\" rowspan=4|'''5'''\n|After a 13-year run with both a Rhythmic and Mainstream Top 40/CHR direction (under the \"Wired\" and \"AMP\" brandings), [[CBS Radio]]'s [[WTDY-FM|WZMP]] [[Philadelphia]] flipped to AC as \"Today's 96.5\", with the station now positioned as a flanker for Classic Hits sister [[WOGL]] and compete against Hot AC [[WISX]] and the top-rated AC [[WBEB]].<ref>[https://radioinsight.com/headlines/110141/wzmp-philadelphia-flips-to-ac-todays-96-5/ \"WZMP Philadelphia Flips To AC \"Today\u2019s 96.5\"\"] from ''Radio Insight'' (January 5, 2017)</ref>\n|-\n|[[Radio One (company)|Radio One]]'s [[Cincinnati]] outlets [[WOSL]] and [[WDBZ (AM)|WDBZ/W268DM]] make format changes. WOSL shifts from Urban Oldies to Urban AC as \"100.3 R&B\", while the former format replaces WDBZ's Gospel presentation, branded as \"Soul 101.5 & 1230.\"<ref>[http://www.allaccess.com/net-news/archive/story/161275/radio-one-cincinnati-refreshes-wosl-wizf-and-wdbz \"Radio One/Cincinnati 'Refreshes' WOSL, WIZF And WDBZ\"] from ''All Access Music Group'' (January 5, 2017)</ref>\n|-\n|After stunting with Christmas music, and afterwards with a [[Donald Trump]]-themed presentation, [[WPBB|WBRN-FM]] Tampa flipped to AC as \"B98.7.\" The station will take on the [[Cox Media Group]] siblings of Mainstream AC [[WWRM]] and Soft AC [[WDUV]].<ref>[https://radioinsight.com/headlines/110158/beasley-launches-ac-b98-7-tampa/ \"Beasley Launches AC B98.7 Tampa\"] from ''Radio Insight'' (January 5, 2017)</ref>\n|-\n|Just six days after [[KKHH]] [[Houston]] flipped to Adult Hits, [[Radio One (company)|Radio One]] dropped [[KROI]]'s pioneering Classic Hip-Hop presentation to pick up the Top 40/CHR format KKHH dropped, billing itself as \"92.1 Radio NOW.\"<ref>[https://radioinsight.com/headlines/110166/boom-radio-now-92-1-debuts-in-houston/ \"Boom! Radio Now Debuts In Houston\"] from ''Radio Insight'' (January 5, 2017)</ref>\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|'''18'''\n|[[Redding, California]] picked up its second Rhythmic Top 40, as KQMS-FM dropped its simulcast of its [[KQMS (AM)|News/Talk sister]] and became \"Wild 99.3\", using the new calls [[KWLZ]].<ref>[https://radioinsight.com/headlines/110305/wild-stunt-in-redding/ Wild Stunt in Redding] RadioInsight \u2013 January 15, 2017</ref>\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|'''19'''\n|[[KFTE]] [[Abbeville, Louisiana]] shifts from Active rock \"Planet Radio\" to Classic rock with the branding \"Classic Rock 105.1.\"<ref>[https://radioinsight.com/headlines/110401/kfte-adds-walton-johnson-and-flips-to-classic-rock/ \"KFTE Adds Walton & Johnson And Flips To Classic Rock\"] from ''Radio Insight'' (January 20, 2017)</ref>\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|'''25'''\n|The Top 40 battle in [[Salt Lake City]] increased to four, as [[KENZ (FM)|KENZ]] dropped Classic Hip-Hop and launches as \"Power 94.9\". The flip brings the format back to the 94.9 frequency for the first time in 13 years, as it was the former home of one of the two Mainstream Top 40/CHRs it will take on, [[KZHT]].<ref>[https://radioinsight.com/headlines/110521/cumulus-launches-chr-power-94-9-salt-lake-city/ Cumulus Launches CHR Power 94.9 Salt Lake City] Radioinsight \u2013 January 25, 2017</ref>\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|'''30'''\n|[[CKBD-FM]] [[Lethbridge, Alberta]] flips from Modern rock to Modern AC while retaining their \"Bridge\" branding.\n|}\n\n===February===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Date\n! Event\n|-\n|rowspan=5|'''1'''\n|Citing a lack of available progressive talk programs for syndication, [[WNYY]] [[Ithaca, New York]] drops the longtime [[progressive talk radio]] format it has held for 12 years and return to its previous oldies format.<ref>Reynolds, Nick (January 15, 2016). [http://www.ithaca.com/news/ithaca/a-progressive-talk-station-goes-off-air-no-it-s/article_edf3db36-d846-11e6-8305-5796b8655f3f.html A Progressive Talk Station Goes Off Air. No, It's Not A Conspiracy.] ''Ithaca.com''. Retrieved January 15, 2017.</ref>\n|-\n|In [[Milwaukee]], Michael Crute, the host of the syndicated ''Devil's Advocate Radio'', purchases [[ESPN Deportes]] affiliate [[WRRD]] and converts it to the first [[progressive talk radio]] station in the market.<ref>[https://radioinsight.com/headlines/116196/madison-host-to-purchase-milwaukee-am-flip-to-liberal-talk/ \"Madison Host To Purchase Milwaukee AM; Flip To Liberal Talk\"] from ''Radio Insight'' (January 27, 2017)</ref>   \n|-\n|After a 24-year run in both mornings and up until January 27 in afternoons, [[Bobby Rich]] is released by AC [[KMXZ-FM]] [[Tucson, Arizona|Tucson]] after he made comments during his program that station management saw as offensive but didn't specify, for which Rich apologized on his [[Facebook]] page.<ref>[https://radioinsight.com/headlines/116281/bobby-rich-let-go-from-94-9-mix-fm-tucson-over-unknown-comment/ \"Bobby Rich Let Go From 94.9 Mix-FM Tucson Over Unknown Comment\"] from ''Radio Insight'' (February 1, 2017)</ref>\n|-\n|Buck Sexton replaces [[Meghan McCain]] as host of [[Premiere Networks]]' evening program, ''[[America Now (radio)|America Now]]''. The move presumably ends his existing program on [[TheBlaze Radio Network]].<ref>[http://www.allaccess.com/net-news/archive/story/162234/buck-sexton-replaces-meghan-mccain-as-host-of-prem \"Buck Sexton replaces Meghan McCain as host of Premiere's America Now\"] from ''All Access Music Group (February 1, 2017)</ref>\n|-\n|[[CJXL-FM]] [[Moncton, New Brunswick|Moncton]], [[New Brunswick, Canada|New Brunswick]] rebrands from XL96 to New Country 96.9 but continues with the country music format. [[CKCH-FM]] in [[Sydney, Nova Scotia|Sydney]], [[Nova Scotia, Canada|Nova Scotia]] and [[CIGV-FM]] in [[Penticton, British Columbia|Penticton]], [[British Columbia, Canada|British Columbia]] also picked up the \"New Country\" branding.\n|-\n| '''2'''\n|[[CBS Corporation]] unveiled plans to merge its [[CBS Radio]] division with Philadelphia-based [[Entercom]], giving that company 244 stations and national reach across major markets, including [[CBS Sports Radio]] and [[CBS Radio News|News Radio]], in a tax-free deal to CBS shareholders through a complex process known as a reverse Morris trust, which begins with an offer to existing CBS Corp. shareholders to exchange their stock for shares in Entercom. The enlarged company will take the Entercom name.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.entercom.com/cbs-corporation-and-entercom-announce-merger-of-cbs-radio-with-entercom-to-create-preeminent-radio-platform|title=CBS Corporation and Entercom Announce Merger of CBS Radio with Entercom to Create Preeminent Radio Platform \u2013 Entercom.com|website=www.entercom.com|accessdate=28 October 2017}}</ref> The deal however will also see CBS and Entercom spinning off stations in Los Angeles (one FM), San Francisco (four FMs, including San Jose), Boston (three FMs), Seattle (two FMs), Sacramento (four FMs), and San Diego (two FMs)<ref>[https://variety.com/2017/biz/news/cbs-entercom-radio-division-merger-1201976392/ \"CBS Sets Radio Division Merger With Entercom\"] from ''Variety'' (February 2, 2017)</ref>\n|-\n| '''13'''\n|[[KTSR]] [[Lake Charles, Louisiana]] drops Top 40/CHR for Classic Rock.<ref>[https://radioinsight.com/headlines/116509/ktsr-lake-charles-flips-to-classic-rock/ KTSR Lake Charles Flips To Classic Rock] from Radio Insight (February 13, 2017)</ref>\n|-\n| '''17'''\n|[[CFJL-FM]] [[Winnipeg, Manitoba|Winnipeg]] drops AC for 1990s' Hits as \"Hot 100.5\"<ref>[https://radioinsight.com/headlines/116584/winnipeg-gets-hot-for-90s-hits/ \"Winnipeg Gets Hot For 90's Hits\"] from Radio Insight (February 17, 2017)</ref>\n|-\n| '''21'''\n|Due to having flipped sister station [[WXZX]] from Alternative to Sports and moving Fox Sports Radio programming to the aforementioned outlet, [[WYTS|WYTS/W287CP]] [[Columbus, Ohio]] flips to Urban AC as \"Vibe 105.3.\"<ref>[https://radioinsight.com/headlines/116621/urban-ac-vibe-105-3-debuts-in-columbus/ \"Urban AC Vibe 105.3 Debuts in Columbus\"] from Radio Insight (February 21, 2017)</ref>\n|-\n|'''24'''\n|Top 40/CHR [[CHBN-FM]] [[Edmonton, Alberta|Edmonton]] retired \"The Bounce\" moniker after 13 years, as it rebrands to parent owner [[Rogers Media]]'s \"Kiss\" moniker.<ref>[https://radioinsight.com/headlines/116707/91-7-the-bounce-edmonton-kisses-its-name-goodbye/ \"91.7 The Bounce Edmonton Kisses its Name Goodbye\"] from Radio Insight (February 26, 2017)</ref>\n|}\n\n===March===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Date\n! Event\n|-\n|rowspan=2| '''1'''\n|[[WRSJ]] in [[San Juan, Puerto Rico]] switched from a [[Tiva TV]] simulcast to a [[News radio]] format, to become \"IBC News Network\", broadcasting international news around the clock, with an alliance between International Broadcasting Corporation, [[France 24]] & [[Voice of America|VOA News]].{{citation needed|date=March 2017}}\n|-\n|Wifredo G. Blanco Pi, the owner of radio stations [[WAPA (AM)|WAPA]] in [[San Juan, Puerto Rico|San Juan]], [[WISO]] in [[Ponce, Puerto Rico|Ponce]], [[WVOZ (AM)|WVOZ]] in [[Morovis, Puerto Rico|Morovis]] and [[WXRF|WGYA]] in [[Guayama, Puerto Rico|Guayama]] acquires [[WMIA (AM)|WMIA]] in [[Arecibo, Puerto Rico|Arecibo]] for $250,000. The regular programming continued until transaction closes and was completed on April 14, 2017. Beginning on May 1, WMIA will become a repeater of the \"[[WAPA (AM)|WAPA Radio]]\" News Network, covering across the island.{{citation needed|date=March 2017}}\n|-\n|'''2'''\n|[[Riverside, California|Riverside]]&ndash;[[San Bernardino, California|San Bernardino]] picks up a R&B/Hip-Hop outlet, as [[KDEY-FM]] breaks away from its simulcast of Classic Hip-Hop sibling [[KDAY]] to become \"Wild 93.5.\" The \"Wild\" brand was last used at [[KRQB]] from 2004 to 2007.<ref>[https://radioinsight.com/headlines/105513/daily-domains-317-is-kday-getting-wild/ \"KDEY Breaks KDAY Simulcast For Urban \"Wild 93.5\" \"] ''Radioinsight'' (March 2, 2017)</ref>\n|-\n|'''6'''\n|[[Springfield, Illinois]] becomes the latest market to pick up a Hot AC outlet, as [[WXAJ]] drops its longtime CHR format to become \"99.7 THE MIX\". The switch puts it in direct competition with [[WNNS]].<ref>[https://radioninsight.com/headlines/116845/wxaj-springfield-gets-mixed/ \"WXAJ Springfield Gets Mixed\"]{{Dead link|date=September 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }} ''Radinsight'' (March 6, 2017)</ref>\n|-  \n|'''7'''\n|KURK [[Reno, Nevada|Reno]] ends its run with Mainstream Rock, as it flips to AC as \"Fun 101\" and changes calls to [[KRFN]]. The move puts them in competition with rival [[KRNO (FM)|KRNO]] for listeners.<ref>[https://radioinsight.com/headlines/116884/k-rock-gives-way-ac-fun-101-reno/ \"K-Rock Gives Way To AC Fun 101 In Reno\"] from Radio Insight (March 8, 2017)</ref>\n|-\n|'''17'''\n|[[Eau Claire, Wisconsin]] becomes the latest market to pick up a Rhythmic Top 40 format, as [[WEAQ]] drops Oldies to become \"95.9 Jamz\" (utilizing the FM translator W240DC [[Chippewa Falls, Wisconsin|Chippewa Falls]]) to counter iHeartMedia's Top 40/CHR rival [[WBIZ-FM]] while serving as a flanker for Adult Top 40 sibling [[WIAL]] and Country sister [[WAXX]].<ref>[https://radioinsight.com/headlines/117024/95-9-jamz-debuts-eau-claire/ \"95.9 Jamz Debuts In Eau Claire\"] from Radio Insight (March 19, 2017)</ref>\n|-\n|'''24'''\n|After three years as [[Nash FM|Nash Icon]] station, [[WKZV (FM)|WZAT]] [[Savannah, Georgia|Savannah]] flipped to Adult Top 40 as \"102.1 The Sound.\" The flip brings the format back to WZAT, having utilized it from 2008 to 2010 when it was \"Z102\" after transitioning from Top 40/CHR.<ref>[https://radioinsight.com/headlines/117122/102-1-sound-launches-savannah/ \"102.1 The Sound Launches In Savannah\"] from Radio Insight (March 24, 2017)</ref>\n|-\n|'''30'''\n|Citing tough competition to attract American advertisers, [[Bell Media]] announced that it would close the US-based sales office of Alternative [[CIMX-FM]] [[Windsor, Ontario]], Canada, which is based in [[Bingham Farms, Michigan]]; the station covers the [[Detroit, Michigan|Detroit]] market. It also canceled CIMX-FM's morning show \"Cal & Co.\", and laid off around a dozen people as part of a restructuring of its Windsor cluster. Despite the changes, CIMX-FM and its sister stations will retain their respective formats.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.detroitnews.com/story/entertainment/television/2017/03/30/closes-american-office-cuts-morning-show-others/99835170/|title=89X closes American office, cuts morning show|work=Detroit News|access-date=2017-03-30|language=en}}</ref>\n|}\n\n===April===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Date\n! Event\n|-\n|rowspan=2| '''1'''\n|[[WBYM]] in [[Bayam\u00f3n, Puerto Rico|Bayam\u00f3n]] switches from [[Spanish Variety]] to [[Jazz]], becoming the third radio station broadcasting Jazz in Puerto Rico (the others are [[WVID]] in [[A\u00f1asco, Puerto Rico|A\u00f1asco]] and [[WIPR-FM|WIPR-FMHD2]] in [[San Juan, Puerto Rico|San Juan]]). Also it would drop the \"Metro Radio\" moniker after two years under a time brokerage agreement with Juan Papotito Rosario (owners of [[WJIT]] \"Radio Hit\" in [[Vega Alta, Puerto Rico|Vega Alta]] and [[WOLA (AM)|WOLA]] \"Radio Procer\" in [[Barranquitas, Puerto Rico|Barranquitas]]) and replaced by \"Radio Jazz 1560\". Also it seeks to reacquire the station from the IBC Divesture Trust to International Broadcasting Corporation.{{citation needed|date=April 2017}}\n|-\n|Two Puerto rican radio companies, International Broadcasting Corporation and RAAD Broadcasting Corporation now operates under a [[Joint sales agreement]] on radio stations [[WIOA]] \"Fresh\" (99.9 FM) in [[San Juan, Puerto Rico|San Juan]], [[WXYX]] \"La X\" (100.7 FM) in [[Bayam\u00f3n, Puerto Rico|Bayam\u00f3n]], [[WQBS-FM|WQBS]] \"Mix\" (107.7 FM) in [[Carolina, Puerto Rico|Carolina]], [[WIOC]] \"Fresh\" (105.1 FM) in [[Ponce, Puerto Rico|Ponce]], [[WXHD]] \"La X\" (98.1 FM) in [[Santa Isabel, Puerto Rico|Santa Isabel]], [[WELX]] \"La X\" (101.5 FM) in [[Isabela, Puerto Rico]] and [[WXLX]] \"La X\" (103.7 FM) in [[Lajas, Puerto Rico|Lajas]], Also the stations offering radio products including its AiLive and La X Radio Visual mobile apps, and digital platforms under the alliance. Also on April 22, WXLX becomes the repeater of the \"Fresh\" CHR radio network.{{citation needed|date=April 2017}}\n|-\n| '''3'''\n|The competition among Rock-formatted stations in [[Sacramento, California|Sacramento]] is about to increase to three, as iHeartMedia's [[KYRV|KQJK]] announced that they're dropping the \"[[Jack FM]]\" [[Adult Hits]] format to become \"93.7 The River.\" The move brings the format back to the station after 11 years, when it was Classic Alternative.<ref>[https://radioinsight.com/headlines/117119/iheart-launch-93-7-river-sacramento/ \"iHeart To Launch 93.7 The River Sacramento\"] from Radio Insight (March 24, 2017)</ref>\n|-\n|rowspan=2| '''17'''\n|After a five-year stint with Alternative rock, [[WJSE]] reverts to Classic Hits as \"106.3 The Shore.\"<ref>[http://radioinsight.com/headlines/117406/yet-another-classic-hits-station-coming-south-jersey/ \"Yet Another Classic Hits Station Coming To South Jersey\"] from Radio Insight (April 11, 2017)</ref>\n|-\n|After 30 years with Country, WHLZ [[Florence, South Carolina]] flips to Adult Top 40 as \"Q100.5\", and takes the new calls [[WQPD]]. The flip puts the station, once known as \"Wheelz 92.5\" (later \"Wheelz 100.5\" in 2003 after the 92.5 frequency was relocated to [[Charleston, South Carolina|Charleston]]) and previously \"100.5 [[Nash FM]]\" after parent owner [[Cumulus Media]]'s rebranding of its Country outlets in 2013, up against iHeart Media Top 40/CHR [[WJMX-FM]] and rival Adult Top 40 [[WSIM]].<ref>[https://radioinsight.com/headlines/117520/whlz-florence-sc-flips-hot-ac-q100-5/ \"WHLZ Florence SC Flips To Hot AC Q100.5\"] from Radio Insight (April 18, 2017)</ref>\n|-\n| '''19'''-'''21'''\n|A series of format flips takes place in [[San Antonio, Texas|San Antonio]]. On April 19, iHeartMedia's [[KZEP-FM]] dropped Rhythmic Top 40 to become Spanish Top 40 \"104.5 Latino Hits\" at 5:30 PM (CDT), which was moved up by a day after rival [[Univision]] countered that upon learning of the flip by dropping [[KMYO]]'s Classic Hip-Hop format to return to the aforementioned format after it was dropped in December 2014 and reclaimed its \"95.1 Latino Mix\" branding by launching it in response at 5PM (CDT).<ref>[https://radioinsight.com/headlines/117551/two-spanish-chrs-launch-san-antonio-within-minutes-one-another/ \"Two Spanish CHRs Launch In San Antonio Within Minutes Of One Another\"] from Radio Insight (April 19, 2017)</ref> The flip of the two stations paved the way for [[Alpha Media]]'s [[KTFM|KTFM-HD2/K277CX]] to drop Alternative \"103.3 The App\" to pick up the Classic Hip-Hop format that was dropped by KMYO, launching as \"G103.3.\" The flip also comes as the ratings for the Alternative format failed to attract listeners, posting a 0.8 in the March 2017 Nielsen Audio book.<ref>[https://radioinsight.com/headlines/117593/classic-hip-hop-quickly-returns-san-antonio-g103-3/ \"Claasic Hip-Hop Quickly Returns To San Antonio With G103.3\"] from Radio Insight (April 21, 2017)</ref>\n|-\n| '''20'''\n|Radio One acquires [[ESPN Radio]] affiliates [[WDCJ|WWXT]] [[Prince Frederick, Maryland]] and [[WXGI]] [[Richmond, Virginia|Richmond]] from Red Zebra Broadcasting. WWXT will become a simulcast of Urban AC [[WMMJ]] (Washington, D.C.) on May 1, while WXGI will retain their current format and simulcast sister station [[WTPS (AM)|WTPS/W274BX]] under the \"Richmond ESPN Radio\" branding.<ref>[https://radioinsight.com/headlines/117572/radio-one-acquires-red-zebra-pair-dc-wmmj-add-simulcast/ \"Radio One Acquires Red Zebra Pair In DC & Richmond; WMMJ To Add Simulcast\"] from Radio Insight (April 20, 2017)</ref>\n|-\n| '''25'''\n|[[Newcap Radio]] plans to sell [[CISL (AM)|CISL]] [[Vancouver, British Columbia|Vancouver]], [[British Columbia, Canada|British Columbia]] to [[Rogers Media]] which in turn plans to rebrand that station to [[sports radio]] as '''Sportsnet 650''' in the fall. This comes as Rogers Media gained full acquisition as part of an agreement in conjunction with the [[Vancouver Canucks]] games previously broadcast by [[Bell Media]]'s [[CFTE]] and [[CKST]].\n|-\n|rowspan=2| '''26'''\n|[[Lansing, Michigan]] picks up a second Top 40/CHR, as [[WLMI]] dropped Classic Hits to become \"i92.9.\" The flip will give rival [[WJIM-FM]] new competition for listeners<ref>[https://radioinsight.com/headlines/117638/midwest-launch-chr-i92-9-lansing/ \"Midwest To Launch CHR \u201ci92.9\u201d Lansing\"] from Radio Insight (April 25, 2017)</ref>\n|-\n|[[WSNE-FM]] in [[Taunton, Massachusetts]] tweaks its format from [[adult top 40]] to a [[rhythmic adult contemporary]]-leaning [[hot adult contemporary]] station, while sticking with the \"Coast 93.3\" moniker and changing its slogan from \"Southern [[New England]]'s Hit Music Station\" to \"Throwbacks and Hits from the 90s, 2000s and Today\". Additionally, WSNE dropped the syndicated shows [[Most Requested Live]] and [[Club Kane]] (which were made with [[contemporary hit radio]] stations in mind) to local programming in order to match the new, more gold-heavy hot AC format.\n|}\n\n===May===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Date\n! Event\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|'''1'''\n|[[Amarillo, Texas|Amarillo]] picks up a Rhythmic Hot AC as [[KQFX (FM)|KQFX]] debuts \"Wild 104.3.\" The station will challenge Rhythmic Top 40 rival [[KQIZ-FM]] and Top 40/CHR [[KXSS-FM]] for listeners in the North Texas market.<ref>[https://radioinsight.com/headlines/117691/wild-104-3-launches-party-amarillo/ \"Univision To Launch Univision Deportes Radio \"] from ''Radio Insight'' (May 1, 2017)</ref>\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|'''5'''\n|After a 4-year run with AC, iHeartMedia's [[WLQB]] [[Ocean Isle Beach, North Carolina]] (serving Myrtle Beach, South Carolina) flips back to Regional Mexican as \"El Patron 93.5.\" Prior to its flip to AC, it was previously known as \"La Que Buena\" under original owners [[Quantum Communications]] from 2005 to 2013.<ref>[https://radioinsight.com/headlines/117746/el-patron-debut-myrtle-beach/ \"El Patron To Debut In Myrtle Beach\"] from Radio Insight (May 4, 2017)</ref>\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|'''9'''\n|After 32 years of ownership, [[Emmis Broadcasting]] sells Rhythmic Top 40 [[KPWR]] Los Angeles to an affiliate of The Meruelo Group for $82.75 million. The announcement comes after Emmis, who exits the nation's second-largest radio market, made a deal in April with its lenders to seek $80 million worth of divestments by January 2018 to amend its credit agreement. As part of the deal, Meruelo will begin operating KPWR via LMA following the expiration or early termination of the waiting period under the Hart-Scott-Rodino Antitrust Improvements Act. KPWR will now be paired with Classic Hip-Hop [[KDAY]] and Riverside-San Bernardino targeted Rhythmic Top 40 [[KDEY-FM]] effective with the deal.<ref>[https://radioinsight.com/headlines/117804/emmis-sells-power-106-los-angeles-mereulo-group/ \"Emmis Sells Power 106 Los Angeles To Mereulo Group\"] from Radio Insight (May 9, 2017)</ref>\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|'''10'''\n|[[Morgan Murphy Media]] acquires CBS affiliate [[KOAM-TV]] [[Pittsburg, Kansas]] and ABC primary affiliate [[KAVU]]/[[Victoria, Texas]] (including its [[KXTS-LD|CBS]], [[KMOL-LD|NBC]], and [[KUNU-LD|Univision]] subchannel/LD-TV outlets) from Saga Communications, who is exiting the television business to focus on its radio outlets, in a $66.6 million deal, which includes an option to acquire Surtsey Media's Fox affiliate [[KFJX]] [[Joplin, Missouri]] and KAVU LMA partner, [[SagamoreHill Broadcasting]]'s  Fox affiliate [[KVCT]], which Saga operates. Saga will use the sale of the television assets to acquire stations from Apex Media, who is selling their radio stations in [[Charleston, South Carolina|Charleston]] ([[WCKN]], [[WMXZ]], [[WXST]], [[WAVF]] and [[WSPO|WSPO/W257BQ/W261DG]]) and [[Hilton Head Island, South Carolina]] ([[WVSC (FM)|WVSC, W256CB/106.5 W293BZ/WVSC-HD2]], [[WLHH]], and [[WOEZ (FM)|WALI]]), but will keep [[WALJ]] in [[Tuscaloosa, Alabama|Tuscaloosa]].<ref>[https://radioinsight.com/headlines/117820/saga-sells-tv-stations-acquires-apex-media-charleston-hilton-head/ \"Saga Sells TV Stations; Acquires Apex Media Charleston & Hilton Head\"] from Radio Insight (May 10, 2017)</ref>\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|'''11'''\n|[[Newcap Radio]] acquires three radio stations in [[Kamloops, British Columbia]] [[CKRV-FM]], [[CJKC-FM]] & [[CHNL]].\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|'''19'''\n|[[JVC Media]] completed its sale of Oldies [[WBGF]] [[Belle Glade, Florida]]/[[West Palm Beach, Florida|West Palm Beach]] to ANCO Media Group; on August 7, JVC moved the Oldies format to [[WSVU]] (replacing its adult standards format), as WBGF (currently in the process of a signal upgrade upon approval from the FCC) flipped to Dance and adopted the \"Revolution 93.5\" branding to mirror South Florida simulcast sister [[WZFL|WZFL-W228BV-W228BY]]/[[WHYI-FM|WHYI-FM HD2]].<ref>[https://radioinsight.com/headlines/117967/revolution-93-5-miami-adds-new-morning-show-expanding-palm-beaches/ \"Revolution 93.5 Miami Adds New Morning Show; Expanding To Palm Beaches \"] from ''Radio Insight'' (May 19, 2017)</ref>\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:center;\" rowspan=4|'''26'''\n|For the first time since it flipped from Top 40/CHR to Modern AC in 2004, [[KQKQ-FM]] [[Council Bluffs, Iowa|Council Bluffs]]&ndash;[[Omaha, Nebraska|Omaha]] brings back the heritage \"Sweet 98.5\" moniker, this time repositioning as \"Omaha's Sweetest Variety\" due to its shift to a more current-based Adult Top 40 presentation as opposed to a Mainstream Top 40 direction utilized during the first incarnation of the \"Sweet\" branding.<ref>[https://radioinsight.com/headlines/118100/kqkq-is-sweet-once-again/ \"KQKQ Is Sweet Once Again\"] from Radio Insight (May 26, 2017)</ref>\n|-\n|Another familiar radio moniker returns as well, this time in St. Louis, where at 10:37 AM (CDT) iHeart Media flipped [[KLOU|KLOU-HD2]]/[[W279AQ]] from Christian Contemporary as \"UP! 103.7\" after 17 months to Urban AC as \"Majic 103.7.\" The flip brings the branding back into the iHeart St. Louis roster, where it had history that began in 1979 at [[KSLZ|107.7]] before moving to [[KLLT (FM)|104.9]] in 1997 and then to [[KATZ-FM|100.3]] in 2012 until its flip to Classic Hip-Hop in November 2014, and where the current KMJM calls reside.<ref>[https://radioinsight.com/headlines/118060/majic-returns-to-st-louis/ \"Majic Returns To St. Louis\"] from Radio Insight (May 26, 2017)</ref>\n|-\n|iHeartMedia also makes changes in Jacksonville and Detroit, where both \"[[Jack FM]]\" branded [[WWJK]] and Mainstream Rock [[WLLZ (FM)|WDTW-FM]] shift to Variety Hits. WWJK adopts \"107.3 The River\" for its branding,<ref>[https://radioinsight.com/headlines/117515/wwjk-jacksonville-drops-jack-branding/ \"107.3 Jacksonville Rebrands As The River\"] from Radio Insight (May 26, 2017)</ref> while WDTW retains \"106.7 The D\" for theirs.<ref>[https://radioinsight.com/headlines/118113/106-7-d-flips-variety-hits/ \"106.7 The D Flips To Variety Hits \"] from Radio Insight (May 26, 2017)</ref>\n|-\n|In [[Nashville, Tennessee|Nashville]], [[WPRT-FM|WPRT-FM HD2/W271AB]] drops Urban Gospel (and after five days of stunting with \"[[Macarena (song)|Macarena]]\" by [[Los Del Rio]]) for R&B Oldies, branding itself as \"102.1 The Ville.\"<ref>[https://radioinsight.com/headlines/118000/light-goes-nashville/ \"Urban Oldies 102.1 The Ville Debuts In Nashville\"] from Radio Insight (May 26, 2017)</ref> \n|}\n\n===June===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Date\n! Event\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|'''2'''\n|[[KCCT]] [[Corpus Christi, Texas|Corpus Christi]] drops its Americana/Texas Country format for rhythmic-leaning [[classic hits]] as \"Retro 104.1\", going up against the more traditional rival in the format, [[KMXR]].<ref>[https://radioinsight.com/headlines/118194/kcct-corpus-christi-goes-retro/  \"KCCT Corpus Christi Goes Retro\"] from Radio Insight (June 2, 2017)</ref> \n|-\n|style=\"text-align:center;|'''5'''\n|[[KFLY]] [[Eugene, Oregon|Eugene]] drops its AAA after two years for country as \"US 101\". The new station will have a battle between long-dominant [[KBUL-FM]].<ref>[https://radioinsight.com/headlines/118215/kfly-flipping-to-country/  \"KFLY Eugene Flips to Country US101\"] from Radio Insight (June 5, 2017)</ref>\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:center;|'''9'''\n|Los Angeles adds another Country outlet, as [[Pasadena, California|Pasadena]]-licensed [[Radio Disney]] flagship KDIS changed call letters to [[KRDC (AM)|KRDC]] and flipped to a country format as \"Radio Disney Country\", becoming the first terrestrial radio station carrying the formerly online-only platform. KRDC also added a translator, 99.1 K256CX, which broadcasts from KRDC's transmitter in [[Irwindale, California|Irwindale]]. The children's radio/contemporary hit radio hybrid continues in the market on [[KRTH]]'s HD2 subchannel. The move also officially ends Radio Disney's coverage on analog AM/FM radio.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://radioinsight.com/headlines/118296/kdis-flips-radio-disney-country-adds-fm-translator/ |title=KDIS Flips To Radio Disney Country; Adds FM Translator |work=RadioInsight |last=Venta |first=Lance |date=June 9, 2017 |accessdate=June 9, 2017}}</ref>\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:center;|'''12'''\n|Univision sells one of its Phoenix rimshots, [[KKMR]] [[Arizona City, Arizona]] (a simulcast of Spanish AC [[KOMR]] [[Sun City, Arizona|Sun City]]), to Educational Media Foundation. KOMR will become an Air1 station and part of a simulcast with KZAI [[Superior, Arizona|Superior]], K243BN [[Laveen, Arizona|Laveen]], and [[KESZ|KESZ-HD3]]/Phoenix.<ref>[https://radioinsight.com/headlines/118315/univision-sells-phoenix-rimshot-emf/ \"Univision Sells Phoenix Rimshot To EMF\"] from Radio Insight (June 12, 2017)</ref>\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|'''14'''\n|Univision sells its [[Albuquerque, New Mexico|Albuquerque]]/[[Santa Fe, New Mexico|Santa Fe]] radio cluster of Rhythmic Top 40 [[KKSS]], Classic Rock [[KIOT]], and Classic Hip-Hop [[KKRG-FM|KKRG]]  to American General Media, who in turn will divest the following properties to comply with FCC ownership rules to new owners: Classical [[KHFM]] to KHFM Community Partners, who will convert the station to non-commercial status, Modern AC [[KVCN|KAGM]] to [[VCY America]], who will also convert to non-commercial and drop the format for Religious programming, and Top 40/CHR [[KDLW]] to BB Broadcasting. AGM will also acquire and sell Univision's Regional Mexican [[KRKE-FM|KJFA-FM]] to Vanguard Media.<ref>[https://radioinsight.com/headlines/118350/american-general-media-acquires-univision-albuquerque-spins-four/ \"American General Media Acquires Univision Albuquerque; Spins Four\"] from Radio Insight (June 14, 2017)</ref>\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|'''15'''\n|[[Fort Myers, Florida|Ft. Myers]] picks up a new competitor for Rhythmic Top 40 [[WBTT]], as WLVO changed their format from Spanish Christian (due to its sale to Sun Broadcasting) to urban contemporary, branded as \"Fly 98.5\" under new [[WFFY]] calls.<ref>[https://radioinsight.com/headlines/118363/hip-hop-fly-98-5-launches-fort-myers/ Hip Hop Fly 98.5 Launches in Fort Myers] Radioinsight \u2013 June 15, 2017</ref>\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|'''19'''\n|Cumulus Media shuffles the formats of its New Orleans outlets, as Alternative [[WRKN (FM)|WZRH]] and [[Nash FM]]-formatted Adult-leaning Country [[WZRH|WRKN]] swap frequencies. WZRH moved to 92.3 and rebrands as \"ALT 92.3\", while WRKN takes over the 106.1 signal and moves from a recurrent-focused approach to a current-based direction.<ref>[https://radioinsight.com/headlines/118439/cumulus-moves-alternative-country-new-orleans/ \"Cumulus Moves Alternative & Country In New Orleans\"] from Radio Insight (June 19, 2017)</ref>\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:center;|'''21'''\n|In a three-way swap, [[WTIL]] 1300 AM \"Radio Util\" in Mayag\u00fcez sells for a transaction from La Mas Z Radio to Wifredo G. Blanco Pi, [[WBYM]] 1560 AM \"Radio Jazz\" in Bayam\u00f3n acquires the station from IBC Divesture Trust to La Mas Z Radio, and also involves International Broadcasting Corporation, receiving land and equipment at the site of WAPA 680 AM in Carolina, PR from Blanco Pi and permission to relocate [[WGIT]] \"Faro de Santidad\" 1660 AM in Can\u00f3vanas to that site and build a transmitter building, and IBC may sell or rent at $600 a month the WBYM transmitter site to La Mas Z Radio. The swap of WBYM and WTIL was completed on August 15.\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:center;\" rowspan=5|'''26'''\n|Summit Media pulls the plug on Top 40/CHR [[W291CL|W261CL & WURV-HD2]] [[Richmond, Virginia|Richmond]] and redirected its listeners to Adult Top 40 sister [[WURV]] after six years (it originally launched as a Rhythmic at [[WJSR|100.9]] before relocating in 2014). On June 27, the station flipped to Sports, giving Richmond its third outlet with the format, joining Fox Sports Radio affiliate [[WRNL]] and the ESPN Radio simulcasts of WXGL/W274BX.<ref>[https://radioinsight.com/headlines/118532/hot-106-1-moving-richmond/ Hot 106.1 Moves Out of Richmond] Radioinsight \u2013 June 26, 2017</ref>\n|-\n|After a year of programming a Mainstream Rock format, [[WUSH-HD2|WUSH-HD2 & W243DJ]] [[Poquoson, Virginia|Poquoson]]/[[Norfolk, Virginia|Norfolk]] (serving the [[Hampton Roads]] area) flipped to soft oldies, branded as \"Vintage 96.5\"; unfortunately, the station dropped the format on September 15 for Sports.<ref>[https://radioinsight.com/headlines/118539/new-vintage-norfolk/ A New Vintage For Norfolk] Radioinsight - June 26, 2017</ref>\n|-\n|Classic Hits [[KOOI]] ([[Jacksonville, Texas|Jacksonville]]/[[Tyler, Texas|Tyler]]/[[Longview, Texas]]) changed their format after nearly 3 years to current-leaning variety hits, branded as \"106.5 [[Jack FM]]\".<ref>[https://radioinsight.com/headlines/118535/jack-comes-east-texas/ Jack Comes to East Texas] Radioinsight - June 26, 2017</ref>\n|-\n|iHeartMedia pulls the plug on another \"UP!\" branded Christian Contemporary outlet, as [[K297AK|K297AK & KXBG-HD2]] [[Loveland, Colorado]] begins stunting with Christmas music. On June 30, the station flipped to iHeartRadio's All-90s format.<ref>[https://radioinsight.com/headlines/118538/christmas-june-northern-colorado/ Santa Brings The 90s Back To Fort Collins] Radioinsight - June 30, 2017</ref>\n|-\n|University of Massachusetts Dartmouth's [[WNPN|WUMD]] signs off at Noon following selling the station to [[Rhode Island Public Radio]]. The 89.3 license is moved to Newport, Rhode Island to relay the public radio network whilst WUMD transitions to online-only broadcasting.\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|'''27'''\n|[[Saint Cloud, Minnesota|St. Cloud, Minnesota]] picks up a Classic Hits outlet, as [[KZRV]] drops Active Rock \"Rev 96.7\" after nearly 10 years to become \"96.7 The River.\"<ref>[https://radioinsight.com/headlines/118523/classic-hits-flows-st-cloud/ Classic Hits Flows Into St. Cloud] Radioinsight - June 27, 2017</ref>\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|'''28'''\n|Amarillo sees another station make a format change, as [[KPRF]] drops Variety Hits \"98.7 [[Jack FM]]\" after nearly 10 years and began stunting with random current hits from various music genres. On June 30, KPRF flipped to Classic Rock, branding as \"Lonestar 98.7.\"<ref>[https://radioinsight.com/headlines/118592/jack-hits-road-amarillo/ KPRF Amarillo Flips To Classic Rock] Radioinsight \u2013 June 28, 2017</ref>\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|'''29'''\n|Adult Top 40 [[WISX]] [[Philadelphia]] drops the format after nearly seven years and flips to a more [[classic hip hop]]-leaning [[Rhythmic AC]] format as \"Real 106.1\". In response to the change, [[Mario Lopez]] and [[Ryan Seacrest]] left the station, but Chio continues as morning host. The flip returns the latter format to the market for the first time since 2010, when WISX evolved to its now-defunct Adult Top 40 format; in addition, the classic hip hop format makes a comeback for the first time since the previous September, when [[WPHI-FM]] swapped frequencies with [[WPPZ]] and shifted to urban.<ref>[https://radioinsight.com/headlines/118603/whats-going-mix-106-1-philadelphia/ WISX Philadelphia Gets Real With Throwbacks] from Radio Insight *June 29, 2017)</ref>\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:center;\" rowspan=5|'''30'''\n|San Antonio sees yet another station shakeup, as iHeartMedia's Top 40/CHR [[KXXM]] drops \"Mix 96.1\" for \"96.1 NOW.\" The move brings the formerly Adult-skewed station to a more current direction closer to Rhythmic-leaning rival [[KTFM]].<ref>[https://radioinsight.com/headlines/118649/kxxm-rebrands-96-1-now/ KXXM Rebrands As 96.1 Now] from Radio Insight (June 30, 2017)</ref>\n|-\n|iHeartMedia also shifts its Adult Alternative-leaning Modern Hot AC [[WDVI]] [[Rochester, New York]] to Adult Top 40, returning to a brand it used 11 years prior as \"Mix 100.5.\"<ref>[https://radioinsight.com/headlines/118645/new-mix-drives-rochester/ \"A New Mix Drives Into Rochester\"] from Radio Insight (June 30, 2017)</ref>\n|-\n|iHeartMedia also pulls the plug on Oldies [[WDIZ|WDIZ/W242BF]] [[Panama City, Florida]], as that station flips to Active Rock as \"96 Rock.\"<ref>[https://radioinsight.com/headlines/118652/iheartmedia-launches-rock-96-3-panama-city/ \"iHeartMedia Launches 96 Rock Panama City \"] from Radio Insight (June 30, 2017)</ref>\n|-\n|The University of Massachusetts Dartmouth's radio station [[WNPN|WUMD]] signs off after 42 years, transitioning to online-only broadcasting. The station's license is bought by [[Rhode Island Public Radio]], which changes the station to WXNI to rebroadcast their feed, and changes the community of license to Newport, Rhode Island.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.southcoasttoday.com/news/20170626/after-42-years-wumd-has-its-final-fm-show|title=After 42 years, WUMD has its final FM show|first=Aimee Chiavaroli|last=achiavaroli@s-t.com|website=southcoasttoday.com|accessdate=28 October 2017}}</ref>\n|-\n|[[Providence, Rhode Island]] [[Contemporary Christian music|CCM]] [[WSTL|WSTL/W229AN]] leaves the air.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.facebook.com/search/top/?q=wstl+radio+ministry|title=Search|website=www.facebook.com|accessdate=28 October 2017}}</ref>\n|}\n\n===July===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Date\n! Event\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|'''1'''\n|Ackley Media Group shuffles the formats of its US Virgin Islands outlets, as American CHR [[WWKS|WIVI]] and Urban Contemporary [[WIVI|WWKS]] swap frequencies. WIVI moved to 101.3 and rebrands as \"Pirate Radio 101.3,\" while WWKS takes over the 96.1 signal and moves from a recurrent-focused approach to a current-based direction, rebranded as \"Kiss 96.1\".\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:center;\" rowspan=2|'''3'''\n|A swap takes places in [[Branson, Missouri]], as siblings [[KRZK]] and [[KCAX|KCAX/K251BX]] exchange formats. KRZK takes back its Classic Country format after having dropping it for News/Talk in 2012 from KCAX, who picks up KRZK's Classic Hits format.<ref>[https://radioinsight.com/headlines/118662/format-swap-ozarks/ \"Format Swap In The Ozarks\"] from Radio Insight (July 3, 2017)</ref>\n|-\n|[[Bloomberg Radio]] makes changes among its [[Boston]] affiliations, as [[WRCA|WRCA/W291CZ]] is announced as the new affiliate; current affiliate [[WXKS (AM)|WXKS/WJMN-HD2]] will continue carrying the network until a new format is announced.<ref>[https://radioinsight.com/headlines/118668/bloomberg-moving-1330106-1-boston/ \"Bloomberg Moving To 1330/106.1 In Boston\"] from Radio Insight (July 3, 2017)</ref>\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|'''6'''\n|[[SiriusXM]] announced that it has fired [[Faction Talk]] personality [[Gregg Hughes|Gregg \"Opie\" Hughes]] after it was learned that he recorded \"a video made of an employee using the [SiriusXM studios'] bathroom.\" In a statement about the action that led to Hughes' dismissal: \"SiriusXM confirms it has terminated its relationship with Gregg \u2018Opie\u2019 Hughes, host of the \u2018Opie Radio Show\u2019 weekday afternoons on the Faction Talk channel. SiriusXM does not publicly discuss internal personnel issues.\" The firing on this date incidentally comes on the third anniversary of the firing of Hughes' former \"[[Opie and Anthony]]\" co-host [[Anthony Cumia]], who was terminated for a series of racially charged derogatory and inflammatory tweets.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2017/music/news/siriusxm-fires-opie-anthony-1202488824/|title=SiriusXM Fires Radio Personality Opie Three Years After Dumping Anthony|first=Shirley|last=Halperin|date=6 July 2017|website=variety.com|accessdate=28 October 2017}}</ref><ref>[https://www.allaccess.com/net-news/archive/story/167357/opie-fired-by-siriusxm \"Opie Fired By SiriusXM\"] from All Access (July 6, 2017)</ref>\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|'''7'''\n|[[Newcap Radio]] rebrands eight radio stations in rural [[Alberta, Canada|Alberta]] to the [[Boom FM]] branding and rebrands [[CFXE-FM]] and its rebroadcasters CFXH-FM, CFXP-FM & CFXG to the \"Real Country\" branding.\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:center;\" rowspan=3|'''10'''\n|Just seven years after a frequency move from 100.7 to 100.3 and after flipping to Classic Rock in 2013, [[WYDL]] [[Middleton, Tennessee]] (serving [[Corinth, Mississippi]]) returned to Top 40/CHR, branded as \"Hot 100\".<ref>[https://radioinsight.com/headlines/118757/wydl-returns-chr/ WYDL Returns to CHR] Radioinsight \u2013 July 10, 2017</ref>\n|-\n|Just nearly three months after The Benns Family announced that it was preparing to sign off and turn its license back in to the FCC after 56 years of ownership, Southern Gospel [[WFLI (AM)|WFLI]] [[Lookout Mountain, Tennessee|Lookout Mountain]]/[[Chattanooga, Tennessee]] was sold and return to the air with Conservative Talk.<ref>[https://radioinsight.com/headlines/117086/wfli-chattanooga-go-dark/ \"WFLI Chattanooga To Go Dark\"] from Radio Insight (March 23, 2017)</ref><ref>[http://www.timesfreepress.com/news/local/story/2017/jul/08/wfli-agatakes-flight/437252/#/ \"Jet FLI AM 1070 back on the air\"] from ''[[Chattanooga Times Free Press]]'' (July 10, 2017)</ref>\n|-\n|Another [[Amarillo, Texas|Amarillo]] station flips formats, as [[KBZD]] changed their format from Adult Top 40 to a simulcast of religious-formatted [[KRBG]] [[Umbarger, Texas]].<ref>[https://radioinsight.com/headlines/118781/radio-grace-expands-amarillo/ Radio By Grace Expands Into Amarillo] Radioinsight \u2013 July 11, 2017</ref>\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|'''19'''\n|[[Northern Kentucky University]] announced that it has sold [[WNKN]] [[Middletown, Ohio]] (whose signal covers both Cincinnati and Dayton at 105.9) to Grant County Broadcasting, who plans to convert the station back to commercial status after six years. The sale mark NKU's exit from broadcasting due to budget cuts and potential loss of funding for colleges and universities from the Commonwealth of Kentucky. NKU had already sold flagship [[WYHH|WNKU]] [[Highland Heights, Kentucky]] (serving Cincinnati) to Bible Broadcasting and [[WPYK|WNKE]] [[New Boston, Ohio]] (serving southeastern Ohio and northeastern Kentucky) to Educational Media Foundation in February.<ref>[https://radioinsight.com/headlines/118890/grant-county-broadcasting-purchases-105-9-wnkn-cincinnati/ \"Grant County Broadcasting Purchases 105.9 WNKN Cincinnati\"] from Radio Insight (July 19, 2017)</ref> \n|-\n|style=\"text-align:center;\" rowspan=2|'''24'''\n|Broadcasting & Programming Systems sells one of its Puerto Rico's Rock stations, [[WCAD]] \"Alfa Rock\" [[San Juan, Puerto Rico|San Juan]], to Educational Media Foundation. Alfa Rock's programming remains on the air until mid-September. Alfa Rock signs off on March 3, 2018 at 12:06 AM. WCAD will become a K-Love station serving the entire island beginning in October 2018.\n|-\n|After a year of AC, [[KXSN]] San Diego flips to Classic Hits, but retains its \"Sunny 98.1\" moniker. The move ends the competition it had with [[KYXY]], who will become KXSN's sister station when the CBS/Entercom merger becomes final.<ref>[https://radioinsight.com/headlines/119077/sunny-98-1-san-diego-shifts-classic-hits/ \"Sunny 98.1 San Diego Shifts To Classic Hits\"] from Radio Insight (July 31, 2017)</ref> \n|-\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|'''27'''\n|After seven years as morning host, [[Carson Daly]] announced that he is vacating that position at Top 40/CHR [[KAMP-FM]] Los Angeles effective immediately so he can spend more time with his family and focus on his television duties. He'll still serve as host of the weekly syndicated Top 40 countdown radio program ''The Daly Download'', which will continue to air and is produced at KAMP-FM, which is the flagship station for the show.<ref>[https://www.allaccess.com/net-news/archive/story/168054/kamp-97-1-amp-radio-los-angeles-morning-star-carso \"KAMP (97.1 AMP Radio)/Los Angeles Morning Star Carson Daly Calls It Quits\"] from All Access (July 27, 2017)</ref>\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|'''31'''\n|Just seven years after flipping to Sports, [[WNMQ]] [[Columbus, Mississippi]] returned top Top 40/CHR and revived its \"Q103.1\" moniker. The Sports format continues on its AM sister.<ref>[https://radioinsight.com/headlines/119062/cumulus-launches-q103-1-columbus-starkville-ms/ \"Cumulus Launches Q103.1 Columbus-Starkville MS\"] from Radio Insight (July 31, 2017)</ref>\n|}\n\n===August===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Date\n! Event\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:center;\" rowspan=2|'''1'''\n|Reno sees more changes take place, as Shamrock Communications exits the market. The company has sold Alternative [[KUEZ|KRZQ]] (licensed to [[Fallon, Nevada]]) to Bighorn Media, who in turn flips its format to Gold-based AC as \"Easy 104.1\" and utilizing the new calls KUEZ. The remaining properties in the cluster, Active Rock [[KZTI]] (licensed to [[Fallon Station, Nevada]]) Top 40/CHR [[KWNZ]] (licensed to [[Lovelock, Nevada]]) and Conservative Talk [[KNEZ (FM)|KNEZ]] (licensed to [[Hazen, Nevada]]) are being sold to [[Radio Lazer]], who will now have a cluster of four FMs serving Reno.<ref>[https://radioinsight.com/headlines/119048/krzq-flip-soft-oldies-shamrock-exits-reno/ \"KRZQ To Flip To Soft Oldies As Shamrock Exits Reno\"] from Radio Insight (July 28, 2017)</ref>\n|-\n|[[Tulsa, Oklahoma|Tulsa]]'s [[KBEZ]] drops its \"[[Bob FM]]\" branding and relaunches as \"92.9 The Drive.\"<ref>[http://radioinsight.com/headlines/119101/bob-gives-way-drive-tulsa/ Bob Gives Way to The Drive in Tulsa] Radioinsight \u2013 August 1, 2017</ref>\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|'''2'''\n|A major shuffling takes place in [[Roswell, New Mexico]]. Majestic Broadcasting's [[KBCQ (AM)|KBCQ/K223BH]] swapped places with sister [[KSFX (FM)|KSFX]], with the latter keeping their Classic Rock format and the KSFX calls (that will now replace the KBCQ calls), while the former dropped Classic Hits for AC and relaunches as \"100.5 Kool FM\" and changes call letters to KZDB.<ref>[https://radioinsight.com/headlines/119120/majestic-shakes-roswell-cluster/ \"Majestic Shakes Up Roswell Cluster\"] from Radio Insight (August 2, 2017)</ref>\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:center;\" rowspan=2|'''3'''\n|Major changes at WAPA Radio, as WGYA/1590 in Guayama changed its historical call letters to [[WXRF]]. Also, WTIL/1300 in Mayag\u00fcez switched its Spanish Oldies format to  News Talk as the newest member of the WAPA Radio News Network.\n|-\n|[[CJCS (AM)|CJCS]] [[Stratford, Ontario]] abandons its 1240 AM frequency  and makes its move to the FM band as \"107.1 Juice FM\" with a [[variety hits]] format while retaining the slogan \"Stratford's Greatest Hits\", becoming the latest radio station owned by [[Vista Radio]] to take on the \"Juice\" branding.\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:center;\" rowspan=2|'''7'''\n|After 10 years of Talk, [[WNNH]] [[Henniker, New Hampshire|Henniker]]/[[Concord, New Hampshire]] returned to its previous Oldies format, which they programmed from its 1989 sign-on until their flip to the aforementioned format in 2007. The move was made due to parent owner Binnie Media taking over operations of rival [[WTPL]] [[Hillsboro, New Hampshire|Hillsboro]] via a LMA<ref>[https://radioinsight.com/headlines/119173/wnnh-drops-talk-true-oldies/ \"WNNH Drops Talk For True Oldies\"] from Radio Insight (August 7, 2017)</ref>\n|-\n|Corpus Christi picked up a fourth Top 40, as former ESPN Radio affiliate [[KLHB]] launches as \"Wild 105.5.\" The station had debuted with a Mainstream direction, only to quickly segue to a Rhythmic direction, giving [[KZFM]] and R&B/Hip-Hop [[KNDA]] new competition, along with challenging Mainstream rivals [[KKPN]] and [[KOUL]] for listeners.<ref>[https://radioinsight.com/headlines/119370/klhb-corpus-christi-goes-wild/ \"KLHB Corpus Christi Goes Wild\"] from Radio Insight (August 20, 2017)</ref>\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|'''8'''\n|After nearly four years with Top 40/CHR, [[WUUU]] [[Franklinton, Louisiana]] (serving the [[Lake Pontchartrain]] and North Shore area between New Orleans and Baton Rouge) returns to its previous Country format and its \"Cat Country 98.9\" moniker.<ref>[https://radioinsight.com/headlines/119191/wuuu-roars-back-cat-country/ \"WUUU Roars Back To Cat Country\"] from Radio Insight (August 8, 2017)</ref>\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|'''16'''\n|After a series of comments which he suggested that [[Black Lives Matter]] protesters should be run over with cars during a June 7 broadcast that drew the ire of [[Major League Soccer]]'s [[Portland Timbers]] and the [[University of Oregon]] Ducks Athletics program,<ref>[http://eugeneweekly.com/blog/portland-shock-jock-uo-sports-flagship-radio-station-called-protesters-be-run-over \"Portland Shock Jock on UO Sports \"Flagship\" Radio Station Called for Protesters to be Run Over\"] from ''Euegne Weekly'' (August 14, 2017)</ref> [[Alpha Media]] announced that it has fired [[KXTG]] [[Portland, Oregon|Portland]] afternoon host Dino Costa after only two months with the station; KXTG is the flagship station for the Ducks and Timbers.<ref>[http://www.oregonlive.com/timbers/index.ssf/2017/08/portland_timbers_distance_them.html#incart_river_index \"Portland Timbers distance themselves from radio partner over commentator's views\"] from ''[[The Oregonian]]'' (August 15, 2017)</ref> The firing also came in the wake of the [[2017 Unite the Right rally|August 12 far-right/white nationalist rally]] protesting the planned removal of a [[Robert E. Lee Monument (Charlottesville, Virginia)|Robert E. Lee statue]] from a [[Charlottesville, Virginia]] park (during which, among other clashes, an Ohio man killed one and injured 19 counter-protesters in a [[vehicle-ramming attack]]), prompting Alpha to examine the matter that lead up to the decision.<ref>[https://radioinsight.com/headlines/119327/kxtg-portland-dismisses-dino-costa/ \"KXTG Portland Dismisses Dino Costa\"] from Radio Insight (August 16, 2017)</ref>\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|'''17'''\n|SiriusXM makes changes in its lineup. The satellite service debuted the 90s/Y2K focused Modern Adult Top 40 PopRocks to XM17, moving [[Sirius XM Love]] to XM70, which bumps [[B.B. King's Bluesville]] to XM74 and moves [[Metropolitan Opera Radio (Sirius XM)|Met Opera Radio]] to XM75; 90s/Y2K focused Active Rock Turbo goes from online to XM41, sending Punk Rock channel [[Faction (Sirius XM)|Faction]] to online; Limited Edition and [[Pitbull's Globalization Radio]] trades places (Limited from 13 to 4 and rebranded as Spotlight, Globalization from 4 to 13), and [[NBC Sports Radio]] is added to XM205. Both [[CNN en Espa\u00f1ol]] and [[Ti\u00ebsto's Club Life Radio]] are dropped from the roster, the latter ending service July 24.<ref>[https://radioinsight.com/headlines/119313/siriusxm-launches-two-new-music-channels/ \"SiriusXM Makes Lineup Changes\"] from Radio Insight (August 16, 2017)</ref>\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|'''22'''\n|[[KVDU]] [[Houma, Louisiana|Houma]]/[[New Orleans]] drops its six-year-old Adult Top 40 format for rock-leaning [[adult hits]] as \"104.1 The Spot.\"<ref>[https://radioinsight.com/headlines/119400/104-1-marks-spot-new-orleans/  104.1 Marks the Spot in New Orleans] from Radio Insight (August 22, 2017)</ref>\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|'''25'''\n|[[Burlington, Vermont]] picks up its first Rhythmic Top 40, as [[WXZO]] (licensed to [[Willsboro, New York]]) drops its Mainstream Top 40 direction to become \"Hot 96.7.\"<ref>[https://radioinsight.com/headlines/119439/burlingtons-planet-gets-hot/ \"Burlington's Planet Gets Hot\"] from Radio Insight (August 25, 2017)</ref>\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|'''29'''\n|[[ESPN Radio]] suspends [[Ryen Russillo]] for two weeks after he was arrested for allegedly showing up naked and intoxicated in a stranger's condominium in [[Jackson Hole, Wyoming]] while on vacation.<ref>[https://www.allaccess.com/net-news/archive/story/169144/espn-radio-suspends-ryen-russillo-for-two-weeks-af \"ESPN Radio Suspends Ryen Russillo For Two Weeks After Arrest\"] from All Access Radio Group (August 29, 2017)</ref> \n|-\n|style=\"text-align:center;\" rowspan=2|'''31'''\n|[[Binghamton, New York]] picks up its first Rhythmic Top 40, as [[WCDW|W225BC & WCDW-HD3]] drops Classic Rock to become \"Hot 92.9.\" The Hip-Hop leaning outlet is expected to take on Mainstream Top 40 rivals [[WLTB]], [[WWYL]], and [[WBNW-FM]].<ref>[https://radioinsight.com/headlines/119526/hot-92-9-brings-hip-hop-binghamton/ \"Hot 92.9 Brings Hip-Hop To Binghamton\"] from Radio Insight (August 31, 2017)</ref> \n|-\n|[[Providence, Rhode Island]] alternative rock station [[WBRU]] signs off at 11:59&nbsp;p.m. from the 95.5FM frequency that it has broadcast from since 1966.<ref name=\"wbruend\">{{cite web|last1=Nunes|first1=Rachel|title=End of an era: WBRU off the airwaves|url=http://wpri.com/2017/09/01/end-of-an-era-wbru-off-the-airwaves/|website=WPRI 12 Eyewitness News|accessdate=1 September 2017|date=1 September 2017}}</ref> The station \u2013 which is owned and operated by the non-profit Brown Broadcasting Services (BBS) organization and staffed by [[Brown University]] students (the school has no ownership over the station) \u2013 sold their license and the frequency to [[Educational Media Foundation]] on August 25.<ref name=\"radioin\">{{cite web|last1=Venta|first1=Lance|title=EXCLUSIVE: Educational Media Foundation To Acquire WBRU Providence \u2013 RadioInsight|url=https://radioinsight.com/headlines/119017/wbru-confirms-imminent-sale/|website=RadioInsight|accessdate=26 August 2017|date=25 August 2017}}</ref> WBRU, its call letters and its intellectual properties were not part of the sale and were retained by Brown Broadcasating.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Bender|first1=John|title=WBRU Could Soon Be Home For Contemporary Christian Rock|url=http://ripr.org/post/wbru-could-soon-be-home-contemporary-christian-rock|website=Rhode Island Public Radio|accessdate=26 August 2017|language=en}}</ref> In a statement on its website, WBRU announced that it would continue operations as an online radio station, with separate 24/7 feeds for both its traditional modern rock format and the hip hop and R&B program that it previously only aired on Sundays.<ref name=\"updates\">{{cite web|title=Updates {{!}} 95.5 WBRU|url=http://www.wbru.com/updates/|website=95.5 WBRU|accessdate=26 August 2017}}</ref>\n|}\n\n===September===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Date\n! Event\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:center;\" rowspan=3|'''1'''\n|Another format flip takes place in Myrtle Beach, as [[WWHK (AM)|WRNN/W288DK]] dropped ESPN Radio for Classic Hip-Hop as \"G105.5.\"<ref>[https://radioinsight.com/headlines/119507/tv-theme-stunting-myrtle-beach/ \"G105.5 Brings Classic Hip-Hop To Myrtle Beach\"] from Radio Insight (September 1, 2017)</ref>\n|-\n|After nearly 18 months with AC, [[WGTZ]] [[Eaton, Ohio|Eaton]]/[[Dayton, Ohio|Dayton]] returned to Adult Hits, this time adopting the [[Jack FM]] branding.<ref>[https://radioinsight.com/headlines/119552/jack-eaton-dayton-alive/ \"Jack Is Eaton Dayton Alive\"] from Radio Insight (September 1, 2017)</ref>\n|-\n|The western suburban areas of [[Milwaukee]] picked up a Rhythmic-leaning Variety Hits outlet, as [[WPTT (AM)|WTKM/W225CP]] dropped Oldies in favor of \"92.9 The Party.\" This will be the second time that \"The Party\" moniker was used in this market, the last being [[WZTI|WZTI/W262CJ]] for eight months in 2015 when it was Rhythmic Oldies.<ref>[https://radioinsight.com/headlines/119559/party-launches-suburban-milwaukee/ \"Party Launches In Suburban Milwaukee\"] from Radio Insight (September 1, 2017)</ref>\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|'''5'''\n|After 2{{frac|1|2}} years with Rhythmic AC, and then Adult Top 40, [[KKGQ]] [[Newton, Kansas|Newton]]/[[Wichita, Kansas|Wichita]] flipped to Country as \"Kansas Country 92.3.\" The flip adds to an already crowded competition that includes current-focused [[KFDI-FM]] and [[KZSN]], and Classic County rivals [[KFTI]], [[KWLS]], and [[KVWF]], the latter who will soon become KKGQ's sister station.<ref>[https://radioinsight.com/headlines/119572/kkgq-brings-red-dirt-country-wichita/ KKGQ Brings Red Dirt Country to Wichita] from Radio Insight (September 5, 2017)</ref>\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:center;\" rowspan=2| '''6'''\n|[[WFAN (AM)|WFAN]] New York City morning host [[Craig Carton]] (who is also part of the ''[[Boomer and Carton]]'' program that airs on [[CBS Sports Network]] alongside co-host [[Boomer Esiason]]) was arrested by federal agents at his home on charges of [[securities fraud]], [[wire fraud]], and conspiracy to commit those offenses. Carton and business partner Joseph Meli are alleged to have run a [[Ponzi scheme]] that defrauded $5.6 million from investors by falsely claiming they had access to millions of dollars of concert tickets at face value through non-existent agreements with [[concert promoter]]s. Carton allegedly used the funds from new investors to cover millions of dollars of gambling debts and to repay earlier investors, according to the complaint filed by the U.S. [[Securities and Exchange Commission]].<ref>[https://www.sec.gov/news/press-release/2017-157 e \"Radio Host Charged With Concert Ticket Investment Scam\"] SEC.gov Press Release September 6, 2017]</ref><ref>[https://www.sec.gov/litigation/complaints/2017/comp-pr2017-157.pdf] SEC.gov Complaint Filed 09/06/2017</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Bekiempis|first1=Victoria|title=Craig Carton, 'Boomer & Carton' co-host, arrested by FBI over alleged $5.6M ticket scam to pay his gambling debts|url=http://www.nydailynews.com/sports/more-sports/craig-carton-boomer-carton-co-host-arrested-fbi-article-1.3473530|accessdate=September 6, 2017|date=September 6, 2017|work=NY Daily News}}</ref>\n|-\n|Due to the threats of [[Hurricane Irma]] in Puerto Rico, Radio stations [[WIVV]], [[WVQR]], and [[WVIS]] in [[Vieques, Puerto Rico|Vieques]], [[WJVP]] and [[WNVE (FM)|WQML]] in [[Culebra, Puerto Rico|Culebra]] were forced to go off the air after [[Puerto Rico Electric Power Authority|PREPA]] received a statement about an electrical outage affecting The Spanish Virgin Islands. On August 12, WJVP, WIVV and WQML resumes broadcasting.{{citation needed|date=December 2017}}\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|'''9'''\n|For the first time since August 2009 when it switched to [[Mediabase]], ''[[American Country Countdown]]'' will return to the ''[[Billboard magazine|Billboard]]'' charts utilizing the [[Country Airplay]] chart. The countdown show had used the ''Billboard'' [[Hot Country Songs|Hot Country Singles]] chart as its official chart from its 1973 debut until the switch to Mediabase.<ref>[https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/country/7898267/westwood-one-billboard-american-country-countdown-kix-brooks \"Westwood One & Billboard Team Up for 'American Country Countdown With Kix Brooks'\"] from Billboard (August 14, 2017)</ref>\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:center;\" rowspan=2|'''11'''\n|[[KZMJ|KSOC]] [[Gainesville, Texas|Gainesville]]/[[Dallas, Texas|Dallas]] rebrands as \"Majic 94.5\" and returned to its Adult R&B format that they aired when it was \"K-Soul\" from 2002 until its flip to urban oldies in 2011, only to shift to Classic Hip-Hop in November 2014; the former was also the same format that was used under the similar \"Magic\" moniker from 2000 to 2002.<ref>[https://radioinsight.com/headlines/119673/majic-back-dallas-ksoc-flips-back-urban-ac/ Majic Is Back in Dallas as KSOC Flips Back to Urban AC] from Radio Insight (September 11, 2017)</ref>\n|-\n|Philadelphia sees yet another format flip, as [[WDAS (AM)|WDAS (AM) & WDAS-FM HD2]] dropped Smooth Jazz in favor of a hybrid Upbeat Variety Pop/Health Information mix billed as \"Breakthrough Radio.\" The concept is a joint venture partnership between iHeartMedia and the [[Children's Hospital of Philadelphia]], who is providing the health programming inserts and features in-between the musical presentation.<ref>[https://radioinsight.com/headlines/119676/iheartmedia-childrens-hospital-philadelphia-partner-breakthrough-radio-1480/ \"iHeartMedia & Childrens Hospital of Philadelphia Partner For Breakthrough Radio 1480\"] from Radio Insight (September 11, 2017)</ref>\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:center;\" rowspan=2|'''14'''\n|[[KOY]] Phoenix changed their format from conservative talk to regional Mexican, branded as \"93.7 El Patr\u00f3n\" (simulcast on FM translator K229DB 93.7 FM, covering the central and southern portions of the market).<ref>[https://radioinsight.com/headlines/119744/el-patron-arrives-phoenix/ El Patr\u00f3n Arrives in Phoenix] Radioinsight \u2013 September 14, 2017</ref>\n|-\n|After five years with Top 40/CHR, [[KQHN]] [[Waskom, Texas]]/[[Shreveport, Louisiana|Shreveport]] returned to Adult Top 40, branded as \"Q97.3\". The move also reversed a format vacancy that KQHN left open since April 2012.<ref>[https://radioinsight.com/headlines/119752/gives-way-q-97-3-shreveport/ I Gives Way to Q at 97.3 Shreveport] Radioinsight \u2013 September 14, 2017</ref>\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|'''15'''\n|[[KVSF-FM]] [[Santa Fe, New Mexico]] changed their format from talk to jazz, branded as \"The Cat\". This brings the format and branding back to the market, where it had a two-year run at [[KSFR|KSFQ]] from 2005 to 2007.<ref>[https://radioinsight.com/headlines/120074/cat-drags-jazz-santa-fe/ Cat Drags jazz Into Santa Fe] Radioinsight \u2013 October 4, 2017</ref>\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|'''20'''\n|Wilfredo Blanco Pi's News Talk [[WAPA (AM)|WAPA]] 680, Government-owned [[WIPR (AM)|WIPR]] 940 and [[Spanish Broadcasting System|SBS]]-owned Urban AC [[WODA]] 94.7 are the only radio stations to remain on the air due to the threats of [[Hurricane Maria]] across Puerto Rico. Some of the local and regional radio stations were destroyed due to loss of communications and remain off the air.\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|'''23'''\n|The [[Voice of America]] celebrated its 75th anniversary with a dinner and dance party at the Voice of America Museum in [[West Chester Township, Butler County, Ohio|West Chester Township, Ohio]].<ref>[http://www.journal-news.com/news/butler-county-voa-museum-gala-mark-75th-anniversary/lCouLCUzlMtDeFSnMA9WJJ/ Butler County\u2019s VOA museum gala to mark 75th anniversary] ''Journal-News'', July 25, 2017</ref>\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|'''24'''\n|The [[BBC World Service]] launches shortwave broadcasts in [[Korean language|Korean]] aimed at the [[Korean Peninsula]] from its transmitters in [[Taiwan]] and [[Tashkent]], which [[North Korea]] quickly begins [[Radio jamming in Korea#Radio jamming in North Korea|jamming]].<ref>[https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2017/09/27/north-korea-aggressively-jamming-new-bbc-broadcasts/ North Korea 'aggressively' jamming BBC's new Korean-language service] ''The Telegraph'', September 27, 2017</ref>\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|'''26'''\n|Entercom announced a first round of divestments in accordance with FCC regulations pending the merger with [[CBS Radio]]. This announcement will see Classic Rock [[KKLQ (FM)|KSWD]] Los Angeles, and country simulcasts [[KARJ (FM)|KSOQ-FM]] [[Escondido, California]] (serving [[San Diego County, California|North San Diego County]] via [[KWFN|KSON]]) and WGGI [[Benton, Columbia County, Pennsylvania|Benton, Pennsylvania]] (serving the southwestern portion of the Scranton/Wilkes-Barre area via [[WGGY]]), change ownership to Educational Media Foundation (which was approved on November 2).<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://fmqb.name/entercom-announces-agreement-to-divest-stations-in-los-angeles-san-diego-wilkes-barre-to-educational-media-foundation/|title=Entercom Announces Agreement To Divest Stations In Los Angeles, San Diego & Wilkes-Barre To Educational Media Foundation {{!}} FMQB|website=fmqb.name|language=en-US|access-date=2017-09-26}}</ref> According to the statement, the three stations will flip to their [[Christian adult contemporary|Christian AC]] [[K-Love|K-LOVE]] network.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://variety.com/2017/music/news/entercom-cbs-radio-educational-media-foundation-1202573949/|title=Entercom Sells Three Stations as CBS Radio Merger Nears Completion|last=Trakin|first=Roy|date=2017-09-26|work=Variety|access-date=2017-09-26|language=en-US}}</ref> The entrance of the Christian \"K-LOVE\" brand into the Los Angeles market would require an agreement with [[Univision Communications|Univision]]'s [[KLVE]], which has used the branding since its debut in 1974.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://radioinsight.com/headlines/119937/entercom-divests-100-3-sound-los-angeles-two-others-educational-media-foundation/|title=Entercom Divests 100.3 The Sound Los Angeles & Two Others To Educational Media Foundation \u2013 RadioInsight|date=2017-09-26|work=RadioInsight|access-date=2017-09-26|language=en-US}}</ref>\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|'''27'''\n|Just nine days after the Regional Mexican format and \"La Jefa\" brand moved over to American General Media owned [[KJFA (AM)|KARS]]/K275AO in Albuquerque and [[KJFA-FM|KSFE]] in Santa Fe,<ref>[https://radioinsight.com/headlines/119811/la-jefa-moves-albuquerque/ La Jefa Moves in Albuquerque] from Radio Insight (September 18, 2017)</ref> [[KRKE-FM|KJFA-FM]] launched a new [[Soft AC]] format, branded as \"Cindy 101.3\" under new owners Vanguard Media, putting it in competition with Cumulus Media's [[KMGA]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://radioinsight.com/headlines/120060/cindy-brings-soft-hits-albuquerque/|title=Cindy Brings Soft Hits To Albuquerque \u2013 RadioInsight|date=3 October 2017|website=radioinsight.com|accessdate=28 October 2017}}</ref>\n|}\n\n===October===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Date\n! Event\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|'''1'''\n|[[Ken Squier]] sells [[WDEV|WDEV-AM-FM]] in [[Waterbury, Vermont]], a station that has been in the Squier family since 1931, to his sales manager, Steve Cormier. Under the terms of the sale, Squier will continue to have a position at the station (including his Saturday morning [[novelty music]] show ''Music to Go to the Dump By'') as long as he pleases.<ref>[https://www.fybush.com/nerw-20170925/ Corm and the WDEV Purchase] ''NorthEast Radio Watch'', September 26, 2017)</ref>\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|'''8'''\n|The radio program ''[[Delilah (radio host)|Delilah]]'' begins an indefinite hiatus, following the suicide of one of the host's sons. [[Rerun]]s will air until the host decides to return.<ref>[https://www.msn.com/en-us/music/celebrity/romance-radio-host-delilah-announces-her-son-zachariah-has-died-of-suicide/ar-AAt1WKs?li=BBnb2gh&ocid=AARDHP Romance Radio Host Delilah Announces Her Son Zachariah Has Died of Suicide]. ''People'' magazine. Retrieved October 9, 2017.</ref>\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|'''9'''\n|Just two months after ending an LMA with New South Radio that saw the Classic Country format relocating to New South's newly acquired [[WHJT]], Flinn Broadcasting flipped the silent [[WJXN-FM]] [[Jackson, Mississippi]] to Classic Hip-Hop, branded as \"Hot 100.9.\"<ref>[http://radioinsight.com/headlines/120270/wjxn-returns-classic-hip-hop-hot-100-9/ WJXN Returns As Classic Hip-Hop \u201cHot 100.9\u201d] from Radio Insight (October 10, 2017)</ref>\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|'''17'''\n|[[Tom Joyner]] announces that he will be ending ''[[Tom Joyner Morning Show|The Tom Joyner Morning Show]]'' when the show reaches its 25th anniversary in 2019.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://radioinsight.com/headlines/120441/tom-joyner-fly-retirement-2019/|title=Tom Joyner To Fly Into Retirement In 2019 - RadioInsight|date=17 October 2017|website=radioinsight.com|accessdate=28 October 2017}}</ref>\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:center;\" rowspan=2|'''20'''\n|With no stunting stations to preempt it, [[WEZW]] in [[Wildwood Crest, New Jersey]], for at least the third time in seven years, becomes the first station in the U.S. to permanently flip to [[Christmas music]] for the [[holiday season]].\n|-\n|[[CKQQ-FM]] in [[Kelowna, British Columbia|Kelowna]], [[British Columbia]] dumps its adult top 40 format and flips to \"103.1 Beach Radio\" with 80s/90s classic hits\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|'''24'''\n|The FCC, in a 3\u20132 vote, approved the elimination of the Main Studio Rule, which was adopted in the Communications Act of 1934 that established the FCC requiring stations to have a studio in its city of license and was modified in the 1970s to allow the studio to be within 25 miles, but will still be required to maintain local or toll-free phone numbers and public file materials that isn't online accessible for the communities they serve. The controversial elimination paves the way for broadcasters to consolidate all programming into a handful of studio locations across the country with little to no content originating in the community or markets a radio or television serves (noncommercial broadcasters were routinely exempted from the rule, and broadcasters regularly leased unused storefronts and other stations' studios as [[legal fiction]]s to get around the rule anyway),<ref>[https://www.fybush.com/nerw-20171030/ NERW 10/30/17: Main Studios? Staying Put, Mostly] ''Northeast Radio Watch'', October 30, 2017</ref> and to fall in sync with present-day technology and social media.<ref>[https://radioinsight.com/headlines/120527/fcc-eliminates-main-studio-rule/ \"FCC Eliminates Main Studio Rule\"] from Radio Insight (October 24, 2017)</ref>\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|'''30'''\n|After a seven-month stint with R&B/Hip-Hop, [[KDEY-FM]] Riverside/San Bernardino reinstated its Classic Hip-Hop simulcast with [[KDAY]] due to the acquisition of Rhythmic [[KPWR]] Los Angeles, which was done to avoid direct competition with its sister station as owners Meruelo Media saw KDEY's Urban format as redundant, despite having done research on targeting the area and to address signal coverage and overlapping issues.<ref>[https://radioinsight.com/headlines/120639/kday-restores-inland-empire-simulcast/ \"KDAY Restores Inland Empire Simulcast\"] from Radio Insight (October 30, 2017)</ref>\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:center;\" rowspan=4|'''31'''\n|Top 40/CHR [[WNOH]] Norfolk exited the format after 6 years and flipped to [[alternative rock|alternative]] as \"Alt 105.3\".<ref>[https://radioinsight.com/headlines/120659/now-105-norfolk-flips-alternative/  Now 105 Norfolk Flips to Alternative]</ref>\n|-\n|With a new [[Madison, Wisconsin]]-centered FM simulcast in place (via W244DR, at 96.7 FM), Mid-West Family broke WOZN away from the \"Zone\" format and launched a new [[alternative rock]] format as \"The Resistance 106.7\" under new call letters [[WRIS-FM]]. The flip returns the alternative format to the Madison market for the first time since 2005.<ref>[https://radioinsight.com/headlines/120654/alternative-resistance-emerges-madison/ \"Alternative Resistance Emerges in Madison,\"] from RadioInsight, 10/31/2017</ref>\n|-\n|After two years with Classic Hip-Hop, [[WKIM]] Memphis began stunting with [[Christmas music]] as \"Christmas 98.9.\" On December 26, the station flipped to AC as \u201c98.9 The Bridge,\u201d giving [[WRVR-FM]] a new challenger in the market.<ref>[https://radioinsight.com/headlines/120662/cumuluss-vibe-begins-christmas-stunt-memphis/  Cumulus' Vibe Begins Christmas Stunt in Memphis]</ref>\n|-\n|Classic Hip-Hop also exits another market, as [[KKRG-FM]] Albuquerque dropped the format after nearly four years and also began stunting with Christmas music as \"Santa 105.1.\" On December 26, the station flipped to Adult Top 40 as \u201cMix 105.1\u201d.<ref>[https://radioinsight.com/headlines/120667/yo-santa-arrives-albuquerque/  Yo! Santa Arrives in Albuquerque]</ref>\n|}\n\n===November===\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Date\n! Event\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:center;\" rowspan=3|'''1'''\n|[[Entercom]] announces that the merger with CBS Radio has been cleared by the FCC and the DOJ, thus paving the way for the deal to close on November 17. The company also announced that it has found new buyers for the 16 stations that they are divesting to comply with FCC ownership rules. Bonneville will acquire through an LMA San Francisco-Oakland's AC [[KOIT]], Top 40/CHR [[KMVQ]], and Urban AC [[KBLX-FM]], San Jose's Classic Rock [[KUFX]], and Sacramento's AC [[KYMX]], Adult Top 40 [[KZZO]], Country [[KNCI]], and Sports [[KHTK]] (under this agreement, Bonneville will manage the stations for one year but must be spun off within 180 days after the merger closes);<ref>[https://radioinsight.com/headlines/120238/entercom-lmas-sacramento-san-francisco-stations-bonneville/ \"Entercom LMA\u2019s Sacramento & San Francisco Stations To Bonneville\"] from Radio Insight (November 1, 2017)</ref> iHeartMedia will add Boston's Urban AC [[WKAF]], Classic Rock [[WZLX]], Conservative Talk [[WRKO]], and All News [[WBZ (AM)]] (which had to ratify a contract with the local SAG-AFTRA in a last minute deal involving the station's employees), and Seattle-Tacoma's Adult Hits [[KJAQ]], Classic Rock [[KZOK-FM]], and Sports [[KFNQ]], all as part of a swap deal that will see Entercom acquiring iHeartMedia's Chattanooga roster of Top 40/CHR [[WKXJ]], Adult Hits [[WLND]], Country [[WUSY]], Active Rock [[WRXR-FM]], and Urban WUSY-HD2, and Richmond's roster of Top 40/CHR [[WRVQ]], AC [[WTVR-FM]], Alternative [[WRXL]], Urban [[WBTJ]], Sports [[WRNL]], News/Talk [[WRVA (AM)]], Classic Rock W241AP/WRVQ-HD2, and Country W253BI/WTVR-HD2 (iHeart spun off Seattle Rhythmic Top 40 [[KTDD (FM)|KUBE]] and Alternative [[KZTM|KFOO]], and Boston Talk [[WKOX (AM)|WKOX]], to a divestment trust as part of a deal to get within ownership limits in the two markets on December 11; both KFOO and KUBE flipped formats on the same day, with KUBE's format moving to KPWK's HD2 sub channel);<ref>[https://radioinsight.com/headlines/120711/entercom-trades-boston-seattle-spin-offs-iheartmedia-richmond-chattanooga-2/  Entercom Trades Boston/Seattle Spin-Offs to iHeartMedia for Richmond/Chattanooga] from Radio Insight (November 1, 2017)</ref><ref>[https://radioinsight.com/headlines/121588/alt-102-9-tacoma-flip/  Alt 102.9 & KUBE 104.9 Tacoma to Flip Monday] from Radio Insight (December 11, 2017)</ref> and Beasley will swap Boston AC [[WMJX]] to Entercom in exchange for Sports [[WBZ-FM]].<ref>[https://variety.com/2017/tv/news/entercom-cbs-radio-justice-department-1202604449/ Entercom to Divest 13 Stations in Exchange for Justice Department\u2019s Approval of CBS Radio Acquisition] from Variety (November 1, 2017)</ref> The sales are expected to close in 2018 upon the completion of the merger.<ref>[https://radioinsight.com/headlines/120705/entercom-fills-corporate-management-ahead-cbs-radio-merger-closing/ Entercom Fills Out Corporate Management Ahead Of CBS Radio Merger Closing] from Radio Insight (November 1, 2017)</ref>\n|-\n|Citing \"inappropriate behavior\", [[Michael Oreskes]] resigns from his position as senior vice president of news at [[NPR]] after three journalists accuse him of sexual harassment.<ref>[http://money.cnn.com/2017/11/01/media/michael-oreskes-npr/index.html Top NPR editor resigns amid allegations of harassment] CNN, November 1, 2017</ref>\n|-\n|[[CJUI-FM]] [[Kelowna, British Columbia]] flips to oldies branded as \"Okanagan Oldies 103.9\"\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|'''6'''\n|After 19 months with Rhythmic AC, [[CFXJ-FM]] Toronto shifted back to a full-fledged [[Rhythmic contemporary hit radio|Rhythmic CHR]] while retaining the \"Move\" branding.<ref>[https://radioinsight.com/headlines/120821/93-5-toronto-moves-back-currents/ 93.5 Toronto Moves Back to Currents] from Radio Insight (November 6, 2017)</ref>\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|'''9'''\n|Country musician Pat Garrett sells Active Rock [[WKHL (FM)|WTPA]] [[Palmyra, Pennsylvania|Palmyra]]/[[Harrisburg, Pennsylvania|Harrisburg]] to Educational Media Foundation, giving the Pennsylvania capital city a K-Love affiliate; EMF is expected to move the format from its translator at 101.7. The sale also ends WTPA's 38-year legacy as a rock station, which began in 1980 at 104.1, followed by a move to 93.5 in 1985, with its final move to 92.1 in 2011.<ref>[https://radioinsight.com/headlines/120892/wtpa-harrisburg-sold-emf/ \u201cWTPA Sold To EMF\u201d] from Radio Insight (November 9, 2017)</ref>\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|'''13'''\n|After ten years as owner and on-air personality at [[WPTY]] Long Island, [[Vic Latino]] is selling his interest in [[JVC Broadcasting]] to his seven partners (worth $301,110.95), but will keep one of the JVC outlets, [[WSVU]]/W240CI/W295BJ West Palm Beach, with him as part of an exchange deal. JVC will continue to maintain ownership of the eight stations in New York State and Florida.<ref>[https://radioinsight.com/headlines/120937/vic-latino-splits-jvc-broadcasting-acquires-west-palm-beach-station/ \u201cVic Latino Splits From JVC Broadcasting; Acquires West Palm Beach Station\u201d] from Radio Insight (November 13, 2017)</ref>\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:center;\" rowspan=2|'''17'''\n|Entercom officially takes ownership of CBS Radio on this date. And along with it flips formats in three markets: In New York City and Dallas-Ft. Worth, the \"AMP\"-branded Top 40/CHRs [[WNYL (FM)|WBMP]] and [[KVIL]] both switched to Alternative as \"ALT 92.3\" and \"ALT 103.7\" respectively; the flips brings the formats back to the two markets for the first time since 2012 in New York City and 2016 in Dallas-Ft. Worth.<ref>[https://radioinsight.com/headlines/121076/alternative-returns-to-new-york-as-wbmp-becomes-alt-92-3/  Alternative Returns to New York as WBMP Becomes Alt 92.3]</ref><ref>[https://radioinsight.com/headlines/121086/and-now-entercom-launches-alt-103-7-dallas/ And Now Entercom Launches Alt 103.7 Dallas] Radioinsight - November 17, 2017</ref> In Chicago, [[WBMX (FM)|WJMK]] ended its run with Oldies/Classic Hits in favor of Classic Hip-Hop as \"104.3 Jams.\"<ref>[http://www.robertfeder.com/2017/11/17/entercom-flips-k-hits-hip-hop-104-3-jams/  Entercom Flips K-Hits to hip-hop '104.3 Jams']</ref><ref>[http://www.entercom.com/going-back-to-throwbacks-chicago-launches-classic-hip-hop-rb-radio-with-the-new-104-3-jams#.Wg8d0GVqaNZ  Going Back to...Throwbacks! Chicago Launches Classic Hip Hop/R&B Radio as The New 104.3 Jams]{{Dead link|date=September 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> And in San Diego, Country [[KWFN|KSON]] traded frequencies with Top 40/CHR [[KSON (FM)|KEGY]], the latter temporarily going online until November 20.<ref>[https://radioinsight.com/headlines/120957/entercom-beginning-san-diego-shuffle-kson-move/  Double Flip Coming in San Diego as KSON & KEGY Promote New Homes]</ref> Later in the afternoon, 39-year Country veteran [[KSWD (FM)|KMPS-FM]] Seattle began playing Christmas music, leading into a flip to [[Soft AC]] as \"94.1 The Sound\" on December 4;<ref>[https://www.allaccess.com/net-news/archive/story/171663/kmps-seattle-flips-to-all-christmas-format-flip-ru KMPS Seattle Flips To All Christmas] from All Access (November 17, 2017)</ref><ref>[https://radioinsight.com/headlines/121486/entercom-flips-kmps-seattle-soft-ac/  Entercom Flips KMPS Seattle to Soft AC] from RadioInsight (December 4, 2017)</ref> that flip later resulted in [[KNUC|KVRQ]] to quickly drop Active Rock on the same day to become \u201cCountry 98.9\u201d and challenge KMPS\u2019 sister [[KKWF]] in the market.<ref>[https://radioinsight.com/headlines/121492/hubbard-launches-country-98-9-seattle/ \u201cAnd Then Hubbard Launches Country 98.9 Seattle\u201d] from Radio Insight (December 4, 2017)</ref>\n|-\n|Cumulus Media pulls the format plug on its two outlets in two markets in favor of Christmas music. After two years with Rhythmic AC, [[WNDX|WRWM]] Indianapolis began stunting as \"North Pole Radio,\u201d while in Green Bay, [[WKRU]] drops Adult Alternative to become \"Christmas @ 106.7\". On December 25, WKRU flipped to Classic Rock as \u201c106.7 The Big Dog,\u201d while WRWM (under new calls WYRG) flipped to Top 40/CHR as \u201cEnergy 93.9\u201d on December 26.<ref>[https://radioinsight.com/headlines/121136/cumulus-prepping-green-bay-flip/ Cumulus Prepping Green Bay Flip] from Radio Insight (November 19, 2017)</ref><ref>[https://radioinsight.com/headlines/121112/from-worst-to-first-to-gone-in-three-years/ WRWM Goes From Worst to First to Gone in Three Years] from Radio Insight (November 17, 2017)</ref>\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:center;\" rowspan=2|'''20'''\n|After six years with Classic Rock, and then six months with Adult Hits, [[WLLZ (FM)|WDTW-FM]] Detroit flipped to Alternative as ''Alt 106.7'', launching with \"[[Seven Nation Army]]\" by Detroit's [[The White Stripes]]. The flip, which come amidst rumors that Entercom was going to flip one of its outlets in the market to the same format, puts them in competition with the Windsor-based [[CIMX-FM]], and gives the market its first U.S.-based alternative rock station since [[WMGC-FM]]'s period as ''105.1 The Edge'' from 1997 until 1999.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://radioinsight.com/headlines/121169/106-7-the-d-makes-late-evening-flip-to-alternative/|title=106.7 The D Makes Late Evening Flip To Alternative|website=Radio Insight|language=en-US|access-date=2017-11-21}}</ref>\n|-\n|President Donald Trump puts an indefinite hiatus on the [[Weekly Radio Address of the President of the United States|weekly Presidential radio address]] after 35 years, citing feedback that it wasn't used to its full potential (the last broadcast was October 13). While there is no official word on whether it is being discontinued, White House Press Secretary [[Sarah Huckabee Sanders]] did leave open the possibility of resuming the broadcasts in the future.<ref>[https://www.allaccess.com/net-news/archive/story/171733/president-trump-puts-weekly-presidential-radio-add President Trump Puts Weekly Presidential Radio Address On Hiatus] from All Access (November 21, 2017)</ref>\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|'''23'''\n|Cumulus Media's [[KAYD-FM]] [[Beaumont, Texas|Beaumont]] dropped its [[Nash FM]] Country format and began playing Christmas music as \u201cSanta 101.7\u201d ahead of a planned format flip and an impending signal upgrade for Classic Country sister [[KYKZ]] [[Lake Charles, Louisiana]] to cover the area. However, on December 26, KAYD-FM returned to its Country format without any explanation.<ref>[https://radioinsight.com/headlines/121227/kayd-beaumont-drops-nash-for-santa/ \u201cKAYD Beaumont Drops Nash For Santa\u201c] from Radio Insight (November 24, 2017)</ref>\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|'''27'''\n|After two years with Classic Hip-Hop, [[WBMO]] [[Columbus, Ohio]] dropped the format and began simulcasting Rhythmic contemporary sister [[WCKX]]. The simulcasts comes full circle, as it expands the \"Power\" branding to its former 106.3 signal after 20 years.<ref>[https://radioinsight.com/headlines/121306/power-107-5-columbus-adds-106-3-simulcast/ \u201cPower 107.5 Columbus Adds 106.3 Simulcast\u201c] from Radio Insight (November 27, 2017)</ref>\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:center;\" rowspan=3|'''29'''\n|After nearly four years as a Top 40/CHR, [[WQMP]] [[Orlando, Florida|Orlando]] flipped to Alternative, branded as \"Alt 101.9\"; they're the third Entercom station to flip to the \"Alt\" brand. This brought the format back to a full-market signal for the first time since 2008, when sister [[WOCL]] flipped to [[classic hits]]. (The most recent station to air the format, [[WCFB|W297BB/WCFB-HD2]], was aired on a [[Broadcast relay station|translator]] and an [[HD Radio|HD sub-channel]], and aired from June 2014 to January 2016.)<ref>[http://entercom.com/press/entercom-announces-return-alternative-rock-radio-orlando-launch-alt-101-9-fm/  Entercom Announces Return of Alternative Rock Radio to Orlando with Launch of Alt 101.9 FM]<