[[Kitchener, Ontario|Kitchener]] and [[CHFI-FM]] in [[Toronto, Ontario|Toronto]]. Also, the station flipped to an All-Christmas music format on the same day as the rebrand before returning to its normal programming on December 26.\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|'''2'''\n|[[John Hockenberry]], former host of [[Public Radio International]]'s ''[[The Takeaway]]'', is accused of sexual harassment by several female co-workers.<ref>[https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/npr-host-john-hockenberry-accused-sexual-harassment-1063771 Ex-NPR Host John Hockenberry Accused of Sexual Harassment By Multiple Former Employees] ''The Hollywood Reporter'', December 2, 2017</ref> \n|-\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|'''4'''\n|Adult Top 40 [[KIOW]] [[Forest City, Iowa]] fires sports director Orin Harris after he was caught making comments with a board operator who also works as a school teacher (and was also fired by the school district) about the make up of how many Hispanic players that were on a rival boys\u2019 high school basketball team during a radio broadcast, then went further by mocking the students\u2019 last names and quoting anti-immigration policy speeches that was made by President Donald Trump, not knowing that the off-air conversation would be streaming live on [[Facebook]] while they were talking.<ref>[http://globegazette.com/news/local/kiow-fires-longtime-sports-announcer-another-producer-for-racist-comments/article_efe6f08b-6417-5eca-a7e1-8eb2e824b31f.html \u201cRacist comments caught on streaming service results in firing of two Forest City radio station employees (with video)\u201d] from Mason City Globe Gazette (December 4, 2017)</ref>\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|'''5'''\n|Classic Country [[KVWF]] Wichita drops the format and joined the growing list of stations playing Christmas music until a new format is launched after the holidays.<ref>[https://radioinsight.com/headlines/121505/hank-packs-leaves-wichita/ Hank Packs Up and Leaves Wichita] Radioinsight - December 5, 2017</ref>\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|'''8'''\n|After six years with Top 40/CHR, [[WRGV]] [[Pensacola, Florida|Pensacola]]-[[Mobile, Alabama|Mobile]] adopted W262BL/WMXC-HD2's urban contemporary format as \"107.3 The Beat\". The flip gives [[WBLX]] new competition in the two Gulf Coast markets.<ref>[https://radioinsight.com/headlines/121607/107-3-wrgv-pensacola-flips-urban/ 107.3 WRGV Pensacola Flips to Urban]. From Radio Insight (December 8, 2017)</ref>\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:center;\" rowspan=2|'''11'''\n|iHeartMedia's Active Rock [[KBPI]] Denver moved from its home of 23 years at 106.7 to 107.9 FM (formerly [[KPAW]], which targets the [[Fort Collins, Colorado|Fort Collins]] and Northern Front Range areas, including [[Cheyenne, Wyoming]], where it moved KPAW's Classic Rock format to 92.9), translator [[K300CP]] (also at 107.9 FM) in Denver, and to [[KBPL|KDZA-FM]] (also at 107.9 FM) in [[Colorado Springs, Colorado|Colorado Springs]] (which also targets the [[Pueblo, Colorado|Pueblo]] area). On December 18, the 106.7 signal relaunched with a Country format, branded as \u201c106.7 The Bull\u201d and new calls KWBL, which is expected to take on established rivals [[KYGO]] and [[KKSE-FM|KWOF]] in the Mile High City.<ref>[https://radioinsight.com/headlines/121387/iheart-begins-three-market-format-shuffle-cheyenne/  iHeart Begins Three Market Format Shuffle] from Radio Insight (December 11, 2017)</ref>\n|-\n|The legendary Rhythmic format of [[KTDD (FM)|KUBE]] Seattle-Tacoma has come to an end as they flip to Contemporary Christian under the KTDD call letters; at the same time as KUBE's flip, sister [[KZTM|KFOO]] drops its nearly two-year-old [[Alternative Rock]] format and flips to smooth jazz under the KFNY call letters. The flips come after the sale of the two stations was announced by owner iHeartMedia as they are acquiring [[KJAQ]], [[KFNQ]] and [[KZOK-FM]] from Entercom as part of their merger with CBS Radio, with KUBE and KFOO needing to be divested to meet ownership limits.<ref>[https://radioinsight.com/headlines/121588/alt-102-9-tacoma-flip/  Alt 102.9 & KUBE 104.9 Move to Placeholder Formats] from Radio Insight (December 11, 2017)</ref>\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:center;\" rowspan=2|'''18'''\n|[[Tegna, Inc.]] announces it will purchase [[KFMB (AM)|KFMB AM]]-[[KFBG (FM)|FM]]-[[KFMB-TV|TV]] in San Diego from Midwest Television for $325 million.<ref name=\"b&c-saletotegna\">{{cite news|last1=Eggerton|first1=John|title=Tegna Buying KFMB TV and Radio Stations|url=http://www.broadcastingcable.com/news/washington/tegna-buying-kfmb-tv-and-radio-stations/170738|accessdate=December 18, 2017|work=[[Broadcasting & Cable]]|date=December 18, 2017}}{{Dead link|date=April 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> The deal marks Tegna's re-entry into radio, as predecessor [[Gannett Company]] had sold its previous radio group to [[Evergreen Media]] in 1997.<ref name=\"ri-saletotegna\">{{cite news|last1=Venta|first1=Lance|title=TEGNA Acquires KFMB Stations From Midwest Television|url=https://radioinsight.com/headlines/121844/tegna-acquires-kfmb-stations-midwest-television/|accessdate=December 18, 2017|work=RadioInsight|date=December 18, 2017}}</ref>\n|-\n|''The Overcomer Ministry'' host [[Brother Stair]] is arrested on eight counts, which include three counts of first-degree criminal sexual conduct and single counts of assault with the intent to commit criminal sexual conduct, kidnapping, second-degree assault, first-degree burglary, and third-degree criminal sexual conduct with a minor.<ref>[http://walterborolive.com/2017/12/update-arrest-of-brother-ralph-stair-confirmed-on-multiple-charges-news-the-press-and-standard/ Update | Arrest of Brother Ralph Stair confirmed on multiple charges | News | The Press and Standard] ''Walterboro Live'', December 18, 2017</ref> The show will discontinue its radio broadcasts on January 1, 2018 but will continue on satellite and its website.<ref>[http://overcomerministry.org/ The Overcomer Ministry official site]</ref>\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|'''21'''\n|Citing his battle with cancer and declining health, [[Charles Osgood]] retires from his radio show ''The Osgood File'' , which had aired since 1967.<ref>[http://www.radioworld.com/news-and-business/0002/osgood-to-retire-from-broadcast/340951 Osgood to Retire From Broadcast] ''Radio World'', December 28, 2017</ref>\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:center;\" rowspan=2|'''26'''\n|[[Chincoteague, Virginia]] picks up a Rhythmic Adult Top 40 outlet, as [[WVES (FM)|WVES]] drops Country to become \u201c101.5 The Mix,\u201d with an emphasis on current hits and recurrents from the 1990s and 2000s.<ref>[https://radioinsight.com/headlines/121302/format-musical-chairs-delmarva/ Format Musical Chairs in Delmarva] Radioinsight - November 28, 2017</ref>\n|-\n|[[Jack FM]] comes to [[Topeka, Kansas|Topeka]], as former [[Salina, Kansas|Salina]]/[[Manhattan, Kansas]]-targeted Oldies [[KSAJ-FM]] enters the market with the Variety Hits format.<ref>[https://radioinsight.com/headlines/120923/ksaj-fm-completes-topeka-move-begins-stunting/ 98.5 Jack FM Debuts in Topeka] Radioinsight - December 26, 2017</ref>\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:center;\" rowspan=2|'''28'''\n|After stunting with Christmas music, [[KVWF]] [[Wichita, Kansas|Wichita]] gives way to Kansas's first Adult Alternative station as \"Flight 100.5\".<ref>[https://radioinsight.com/headlines/121505/hank-packs-leaves-wichita/ Flight 100.5 Takes Off In Wichita With AAA] Radioinsight - January 1, 2018</ref>\n|}\n\n==Debuts==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Date\n! Event\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|'''April 20'''\n|[[Univision]] launched [[Univision Deportes Radio]] on ten of its owned and operated stations. The Spanish-language network plans to utilize their extensive coverage of soccer games as the basis of their programming and to counter the offerings from [[ESPN Deportes]].<ref>[https://radioinsight.com/headlines/109792/univision-to-launch-univision-deportes-radio/ \"Univision To Launch Univision Deportes Radio\"] from ''Radio Insight'' (December 19, 2016)</ref>\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|'''May 18'''\n|[[The Beatles Channel]], a new full-time station licensed and authorized by [[Apple Corps]] featuring music from the \"[[The Beatles|Fab Four]]\" as well as their solo material, debuts on [[SiriusXM]], broadcasting on XM18.<ref>[https://radioinsight.com/headlines/117695/siriusxm-launches-bealtes-channel/ \"SiriusXM Launches The Bealtes Channel\"] from Radio Insight (May 2, 2017)</ref> \n|-\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|'''May 25'''\n|Envision Networks and [[Weigel Broadcasting]] begins expanding the Oldies format of [[WRME-LP]] [[Chicago]], broadcasting under the \"[[MeTV|MeTV FM]]\" branding nationwide.<ref>[https://www.allaccess.com/net-news/archive/story/166079/chicago-s-metv-fm-format-available-nationally-via- \"Chicago's MeTV FM Format Available Nationally Via Envision Networks\"] from All Access Music Group (May 25, 2017)</ref>\n|}\n\n==Closings==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Date\n! Event\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|'''January 2'''\n|A storm folds the tower of [[WGPC]] in [[Albany, Georgia]] in half, taking the station silent.<ref name=\"walb-wgpcoff\">{{cite news|last1=Miller|first1=Dave|title=Albany's first radio tower wrecked by storm winds|url=http://www.walb.com/story/34234877/albanys-first-radio-tower-wrecked-by-storm-winds|accessdate=March 22, 2017|work=[[WALB|WALB.com]]|date=January 11, 2017|language=en}}</ref> On March 22, owner Cumulus Media announced that the WGPC license would be returned to the Federal Communications Commission.<ref name=\"walb-wgpcdefunct\">{{cite news|last1=Miller|first1=Dave|title=Albany's first radio station gone-- for good|url=http://www.walb.com/story/34971131/albanys-first-radio-station-gone-for-good|accessdate=March 22, 2017|work=[[WALB|WALB.com]]|date=March 22, 2017|language=en}}</ref> WGPC was Albany's first radio station.<ref name=\"walb-wgpcoff\"/>\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|'''January 11'''\n|Norway was scheduled to become the first country to discontinue  FM broadcasts, as it officially flips the switch to Digital Audio Broadcasting for Radio. This move, albeit controversial, is being watched by other countries to see if this transition works.<ref>[https://www.bbc.com/news/technology-38529435 \"Norway's controversial radio switch-off\"] from [[BBC]] (January 6, 2017)</ref>\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|'''January 26'''\n|Comedian/actor [[Jay Mohr]] announced that he is ending his fan-based program ''Jay Mohr Sports'' and is exiting [[Fox Sports Radio]] after three years to focus on his family and other projects. His co-hosts [[Dan Beyer]] and Jonas Knox will continue as interim host until a new replacement is announced.<ref>[http://www.allaccess.com/net-news/archive/story/162067/jay-mohr-exits-fox-sports-radio \"Jay Mohr Exits Fox Sports Radio\"] from ''All Access Radio Group'' (January 26, 2017)</ref>\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|'''January 28'''\n|After 30 years as the original host and creator of ''[[Open House Party]]'', [[John Garabedian]] retires from radio with his last broadcast.<ref>[http://www.allaccess.com/net-news/archive/story/162144/john-garabedian-hangs-up-his-open-house-party-head \"John Garabedian Hangs Up His 'Open House Party' Headphones\"] from ''All Access Music Group'' (January 31, 2017)</ref>\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|'''January 31'''\n|[[Radio Australia]] shuts down its [[Shortwave radio|shortwave]] service after 73 years.<ref>[http://www.sheppnews.com.au/2017/02/01/71659/radio-goes-quiet Radio goes quiet] ''Shepparton News'', February 1, 2017</ref>\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|'''February 8'''\n|After a facing a series of legal challenges stemming from an incident in which a contestant died from water intoxication during a contest in 2007 that lead to the family awarded $25 Million in damages in 2009, thus triggering a possible revoking of its license, [[Entercom]] announced that they would be voluntarily handing in the [[KDND]] [[Sacramento, California|Sacramento]] broadcast license to the FCC, taking KDND off the air permanently and opening their FM frequency (107.9) for new applications for this frequency (a process that will take three to five years). The format and calls, including \"The End\" moniker will relocate to [[KUDL]] on February 6, 2017, bringing the Top 40/CHR format back to the 106.5 signal for the first time since KUDL's predecessor KWOD transitioned to Alternative in 1993. The move also clears a hurdle in the announced merger between Entercom and [[CBS Radio]], as their Sacramento roster of stations must divest itself of three FM properties in the market.<ref>[https://radioinsight.com/headlines/108908/kdnd-license-renewal-hearing-to-be-held-before-administrative-law-judge/ \"Entercom To Turn In KDND Sacramento License; Move CHR Format To 106.5\"] from ''Radio Insight'' (February 4, 2017)</ref><ref>[http://www.sacbee.com/news/local/article130697129.html \"It\u2019s the end of The End 107.9. Format will move down the dial ahead of planned merger\"] from ''[[The Sacramento Bee]]'' (February 3, 2017)</ref>\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|'''February 18'''\n|After 25 years, the Classical formatted [[W-BACH]] Network, which at its height served the Southern, Central and Down East portions of [[Maine]], signs off the air. The stations that simulcast it became simulcasts of parent company Binnie Media's sister outlets, with WBQX [[Thomaston, Maine|Thomaston]] simulcasting Classic Hits [[WFNK]] [[Lewiston, Maine|Lewiston]] and W245AA [[Portland, Maine|Portland]] simulcasting Country sister [[WTHT]] [[Auburn, Maine|Auburn]].<ref>[https://radioinsight.com/headlines/116595/w-bach-signs-off-in-maine/ \"W-BACH Signs Off In Maine\"] from Radio Insight (February 20, 2017)</ref> \n|-\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|'''February 28'''\n|[[KNIT (AM)|KFNZ]] [[Salt Lake City, Utah|Salt Lake City]] signed off the air after 95 years; Cumulus had planned to turn the license in to the FCC, but requested a STA to leave it silenced pending a sale of the transmitter equipment and the license to another owner. The announcement comes with the ending its 21-year run with a Sports talk format and a three-year affiliation with [[CBS Sports Radio]].<ref>[https://radioinsight.com/headlines/116788/kfnz-salt-lake-city-goes-dark/ \"KFNZ Salt Lake City Goes Dark\"] from Radio Insight (February 28, 2017)</ref>\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:center;\" rowspan=2|'''March 31'''\n|[[Fox Sports Radio]] affiliate [[KCOE (AM)|KICE]] [[Bend, Oregon]] leaves the air and its license deleted after 58 years. FM sister [[KICE (FM)|KOCE]], which simulcasted KICE, will direct listeners to the 94.9 signal and take the KICE calls.<ref>[https://radioinsight.com/headlines/117188/kice-bend-joins-parade-ams-going-dark/ \"KICE Bend Joins Parade Of AMs Going Dark\"] from Radio Insight (March 29, 2017)</ref>\n|-\n|After a 17-year run, [[Entercom]] Rhythmic Top 40 [[KQKS]] [[Lakewood, Colorado|Lakewood]]/[[Denver]] confirmed that its morning team of Larry Ulibarri and Kathie Jay are no longer with the station after the two parties failed to come to terms on a new contract. The morning team's third partner, Kendall B., left KQKS in January to pursue other opportunities. KQKS plans to fill the morning slot with its current staffers until an announcement is made.<ref>[http://www.westword.com/news/entercom-cancels-1075-morning-show-with-larry-and-kathie-after-contract-dispute-8926803 \"KS 107.5 Morning Show With Larry and Kathie Canceled After Contract Dispute\"] from ''Westword'' (March 30, 2017)</ref>\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|'''May 1'''\n|[[WENN (AM)|WENN]] [[Birmingham, Alabama|Birmingham]] signs off the air after 67 years. The move also ends its run with the AC format it was programming via FM Translator W271BN, which owner Summit Media sold to [[Educational Media Foundation]], however, three days later, WENN returned to the air broadcasting [[Soft rock|Soft AC]].<ref>[https://radioinsight.com/headlines/117714/easy-102-1-birmingham-signs-off/ \"Easy 102.1 Birmingham Signs-Off\"] from Radio Insight (May 3, 2017)</ref>\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|'''May 3'''\n|[[Frank Deford]] delivers his last commentary for [[NPR]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.npr.org/2017/05/03/526582433/deford-says-thanks-for-a-good-game-drops-mic|title=Deford Says Thanks For A Good Game, Drops Mic|website=npr.org|accessdate=28 October 2017}}</ref>\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|'''May 7'''\n| As part of an AM revitalization plan, the FCC plans to shut down Puerto Rican AM synchronized stations located at [[WA2XPA]] [[Arecibo, Puerto Rico|Arecibo]], [[WI2XSO]] [[Mayag\u00fcez, Puerto Rico|Mayag\u00fcez]], [[WI3XSO]] [[Aguadilla, Puerto Rico|Aguadilla]] and [[WI2XAC]] [[Ponce, Puerto Rico|Ponce]]. Radio stations [[WAPA (AM)|WAPA]] and [[WIAC (AM)|WIAC]] in [[San Juan, Puerto Rico|San Juan]] and [[WISO]] in Ponce petitioned to allow the licenses cancelled by that date.\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|'''June 30'''\n|After a two-year tenure with the station, and due to tensions with [[WLZD-LP]] General Manager Sam Neace, East Kentucky DJs \"Jammin\" Jon Colwell and Jack \"Jack Attack\" Caudill decide to combine both ''Flashback Fridays'' and ''Throwback With Jack Attack'' into one final show. With one hour left, Neace made the decision to pull the plug on the farewell show. Despite being pulled, the DJ's traveled to the station and said their goodbyes to their respective fanbases on the air. This incident also ends Colwell and Neace's Five-Year Working Relationship. \n|-\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|'''July 24'''\n|After 17 years, online Dance station Music One shuts down operations, citing declining listenership and increasing costs of being a non-profit entity on the air.<ref>[http://www.musicone.fm A goodbye message from Music One] posted July 24, 2017</ref>\n|-\n|style=\